# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: angelica-schwall-düren
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] From 2002 to 2010, she was deputy chairwoman of the SPD parliamentary group in the Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] On 15 July 2010 she was appointed Minister for Federal Affairs, Europe and Media of North Rhine-Westphalia in the first cabinet of Minister-President Hannelore Kraft.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] On 21 June 2012 she was also appointed to this position in the second cabinet of Minister-President Hannelore Kraft and held this office until 1 October 2015.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] After graduating from high school in Offenburg in 1967 Schwall-Düren studied history, political science and French as a teacher in Freiburg im Breisgau, Montpellier and Münster, which she completed in 1973 with the first state examination for teaching at grammar schools.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] She then worked as a research assistant at the University of Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] In 1977 she completed her doctorate at the University of Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] From 1979 to 1994 she was a member of the local council in her hometown of Metelen.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] She was a member of the German Bundestag from 1994 to 2010.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] From 1998 to 2002 she was Parliamentary Secretary of the SPD parliamentary group.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] From October 2002 until she joined the North Rhine-Westphalian state government on 15 July 2010 she was deputy leader of the parliamentary group responsible for European Union affairs.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/angelica-schwall-düren] She has been a representative for the state of North Rhine-Westphalia, on the Deutschlandradio Board of Directors since 2014.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The **Bundestag** (German: [ˈbʊndəstaːk] ⓘ, 'Federal Diet') is the federal parliament of Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] It is the only constitutional body in the country directly elected by the German people.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag was established by Title III of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (*Grundgesetz*) in 1949 as one of the legislative bodies of Germany, the other being the Bundesrat.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The members of the Bundestag are representatives of the German people as a whole, are not bound by any orders or instructions and are only accountable to their conscience.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Since the current 21st legislative period, the Bundestag has a fixed number of 630 members.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected every four years by German citizens aged 18 and older.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Elections use a mixed-member proportional representation system which combines first-past-the-post voting for constituency-seats with proportional representation to ensure its composition mirrors the national popular vote.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The German Bundestag cannot dissolve itself; only the president of Germany can do so under certain conditions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of government at the federal level.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag is considerably more powerful than the Bundesrat, which represents the state governments.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] All bills must first be passed in the Bundestag before they are discussed in the Bundesrat.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundesrat can only accept laws passed by the Bundestag without amendment.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Only in some areas, where laws directly affect the states, can the Bundesrat reject laws; otherwise, it can only lodge an objection to them, which the Bundestag can overrule.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Above all, however, the chancellor and the federal government are solely responsible to the Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag also has sole budgetary authority.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Since 1999, the Bundestag has met in the Reichstag building in Berlin.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag also operates in multiple new government buildings in Berlin around the neo-renaissance house and has its own police force (the *Bundestagspolizei*), directly subordinated to the Bundestag Presidency.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag's presiding officer is the president of the Bundestag; they are deputized by the Vice Presidents of the Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Since 2025, Julia Klöckner of the CDU/CSU is the president of the Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In the protocol order of the federation, the President of the Bundestag ranks second after the President and before the Chancellor.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The first body to be called Bundestag was the legislative body of the German Confederation, which convened in Frankfurt am Main from 1816 to 1866.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] This Bundestag was a convention of state envoys.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] During the revolution of 1848/49, the National Assembly, which met in Frankfurt am Main, was the first elected German parliament and served as a constituent assembly for a German state, which ultimately did not come to pass.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The North German Confederation, founded in 1866/67, was the first German nation state with an established elected parliament, however this ended up being called the Reichstag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In 1870/71, the federation was expanded to include the southern German territories and was henceforth called the German Empire.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Reichstag building, where the current Bundestag meets since 1999 (see below), was built in 1888.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The German Empire was not yet a parliamentary democracy in the modern sense, but a constitutional monarchy with democratic elements.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Reichstag had to approve all bills, had the right to initiate legislation and, in particular, had budgetary sovereignty.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] However, the Chancellor and the imperial government were not responsible to parliament, but to the emperor alone.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] It was not until 1918, a few weeks before the end of the First World War, that the Reichstag was given the right, as part of a constitutional reform, to withdraw its confidence in the Chancellor and thus force him to resign.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] There was also no universal suffrage for the Reichstag; only men over the age of 25 were entitled to vote in Reichstag elections.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] After its defeat in the First World War, Germany became a republic and a parliamentary democracy with the Weimar Constitution of 1919.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The voting age was lowered to 21 years and women were given the right to vote for (and serve in) the Reichstag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] However, the first German democracy failed for various reasons, some of which were directly related to the Reichstag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The pure proportional representation system in elections did not produce clear majorities and the various parties were not sufficiently willing to compromise to form stable governments.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] This led to numerous changes of government and snap elections.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In the last years of the Weimar Republic, opposition parties on the far-right and the far-left held the majority of seats in the Reichstag, which led the governments to rule largely by emergency decrees and bypass parliament.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In 1933, Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor and through the Reichstag Fire Decree, the Enabling Act of 1933 and the death of President Paul von Hindenburg in 1934, gained unlimited power.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] After this, the Reichstag, in which only the Nazi Party was represented from November 1933 on, met only rarely, above all to extend the emergency laws on which the Nazi dictatorship was formally based.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] With the Basic Law of 1949, Germany's second democratic constitution, the Bundestag was established as the new parliament.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Due to the division of Germany, the Bundestag was de facto a West German parliament until 1990.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The socialist GDR in East Germany had its own parliament, the Volkskammer, which, however, did not emerge from democratic elections except for its last electoral term in 1990.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Because West Berlin was not officially under the jurisdiction of the Basic Law during the division, the Bundestag met in Bonn in several different buildings, including (provisionally) a former waterworks facility and finally in the Bundeshaus.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In addition, owing to the city's legal status, citizens of West Berlin were unable to vote in elections to the Bundestag, and were instead represented by 22 non-voting delegates chosen by the House of Representatives, the city's legislature.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Since German reunification in 1990, the Bundestag has once again been an all-German parliament.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In 1999, the German parliament moved from Bonn to Berlin and sits once again in the Reichstag building.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of the German political system.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag is one of three constitutional bodies (along with the Bundesrat and the federal government) that have the right of initiative for the legislative process.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In order to introduce a bill in the Bundestag, the support of a faction or of a number of MPs corresponding to at least 5% of all MPs is required.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] All bills (including those introduced by the Bundesrat and the government) are first voted on in the Bundestag (for bills from the Bundesrat and the government, however, an opinion must first be obtained from the other body).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] A bill is first discussed at first reading, then referred to one or more committees, where it can be amended; the resulting committee version then goes back to the plenary, where it is passed at second and third reading.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Amendments can also be tabled at this stage.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] A simple majority (more yes votes than no votes with no regard to abstentions) is required for normal legislative proposals.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In some very rare cases, the Basic Law requires the so-called chancellor majority (majority of all members of parliament) for simple laws, for example to establish new intermediate and subordinate federal authorities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Laws amending the Basic Law require a two-thirds majority of all members of the Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] A law passed by the Bundestag is passed on to the Bundesrat.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Amendments to the Basic Law and laws that directly affect the states must be passed by the Bundesrat by majority vote (amendments to the Basic Law, again, by a two-thirds majority); all other laws are considered passed if the Bundesrat does not object to them within 14 days.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In no case can the Bundesrat make amendments to a bill.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] If the Bundesrat rejects a bill, the matter is often referred to the so-called mediation committee, a body made up of an equal number of members of the Bundestag and Bundesrat, which attempts to negotiate whether the bill can find the approval of both chambers with certain amendments.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] A version amended in this way must then be passed again by a majority in both chambers in order to become law (in this case the rules of procedure of both chambers provide for an abbreviated legislative procedure).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In the final step, a law must be signed by the President of Germany (they have a right of veto in theory, but this has been used very rarely in the history of the Federal Republic).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag has an elective function for a number of offices.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The chancellor is elected by the Bundestag and formally appointed by the president of Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] A chancellor's election is necessary whenever the office of chancellor has fallen vacant.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] This is the case if a newly elected Bundestag meets for the first time, or during legislative periods, if the former chancellor died or resigned.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The chancellor's election is one of the few cases in which a vote in the Bundestag requires a majority of all elected members, not just a majority of those assembled at the time, the so-called *Kanzlermehrheit* ("chancellor majority").
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] As with other elections performed by the Bundestag, the chancellor is elected via secret ballot.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] If the nominee reaches the necessary "chancellor majority", the president appoints him or her and, after that, the president of the Bundestag will administer the oath of office before the assembled house.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] If this nominee is not elected, the right of nomination is transferred onto the Bundestag: Candidates can now be nominated for election, whereby a nomination must be supported by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag can hold any number of ballots in this manner for two weeks.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] To be elected, a candidate still needs a "chancellor majority" of yes-votes ("Second voting phase").
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] If the Bundestag is unable to elect a chancellor in these fourteen days, a final ballot is held on the very next day.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Once again, candidates can be nominated by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Candidates receiving a "chancellor majority" in this ballot are elected.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Otherwise, it is up to the President of Germany either to appoint the candidate with the plurality of votes as Chancellor or to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections ("Third voting phase").
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Another possibility to vote a new chancellor into office is the constructive vote of no confidence, which allows the Bundestag to replace a sitting chancellor, if it elects a new chancellor with the "chancellor-majority".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag shares responsibility with the Bundesrat for electing the judges of the Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Both chambers elect four judges to each of the court's two senates.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] They also elect the president and vice-president of the Federal Constitutional Court in alternating order.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In the Bundestag, this requires a two-thirds majority of members present, which has equal at least a majority of all members.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The majority ratios in the Bundestag therefore do not necessarily have to correspond to those in the Federal Assembly.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected for four years, and new elections must be held no earlier than 46 and no later than 48 months after the beginning of a given legislative term.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] By way of exception, there may be an early election if the President of Germany dissolves the Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] However, the President only has the right to do so in the event of a failed chancellor election or if an incumbent chancellor requests dissolution after losing a vote of confidence.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The possibility of an early election is therefore in theory much more limited than is the case in some other parliamentary democracies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] This restriction is intended to encourage the parliamentary groups to cooperate in difficult situations, and is a lesson learned from the experience of the Weimar Republic, in which snap elections were very frequent because the parties were unable to compromise and form stable governments.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] A legislative term ends at the moment when a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for the first time, which must occur within 30 days after an election.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The principle applies that there can be no "period without parliament".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] An elected Bundestag is fully competent to act until a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for its first session.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Prorogations and dissolutions (in the strict sense), as known in the Westminster system, do not exist in Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Even an early dissolution of the Bundestag, as described above, in practice only leads to an early election, but does not end the legislative period itself.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Following the tradition of German parliamentarism, the Bundestag is subject to the *principle of discontinuation*, meaning that a newly-elected Bundestag is legally regarded as a body and entity completely different from the previous Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] This leads to the result that any motion, application or action submitted to the previous Bundestag, e.g. a bill referred to the Bundestag by the Federal Government, is regarded as void by non-decision (German terminology: "*Die Sache fällt der Diskontinuität anheim*").
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Thus any bill that has not been decided upon by the beginning of the new electoral period must be brought up by the government again if it aims to uphold the motion, this procedure in effect delaying the passage of the bill.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Furthermore, any newly-elected Bundestag will have to freshly decide on the rules of procedure (*Geschäftsordnung*), which is done by a formal decision of taking over such rules from the preceding Bundestag by reference.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] If the succeeding Bundestag convenes with same or similar majorities like its predecessor, the parliament can decide to take over earlier initiatives of legislation in the same fashion to abbreviate the process, thus effectively breaking the principle of discontinuation by a pull.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Before an electoral reform in 2023, the Bundestag nominally had 598 members, with the mixture of majority and proportional representation regularly leading to a large number of additional overhang and compensation mandates.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Every elector has two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a party list vote (second vote).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The second votes are used to produce proportionality with respect to the total number of 630 seats; first at the federal level and then at state level (using the Sainte-Laguë method).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In most cases, the number of constituencies won by a party in a given state does not exactly correspond to the number of seats to which the party is entitled in that state via second votes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] To qualify for any seats, however, a party must either win three single-member constituencies via first votes (basic mandate clause) or exceed a threshold of 5% of the second votes nationwide.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] This does not apply to independent constituency candidates: these always enter the Bundestag if they win their constituency.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] (However, no independent constituency candidate has won a constituency since 1949).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Seats allocated in this way are subtracted from the base number of 630 when the mandates are distributed among the parties.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In addition, the second votes of voters who have elected a successful independent candidate in a constituency are not taken into account when calculating the number of mandates (although they are for the 5% threshold).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Parties representing recognized national minorities (currently Danes, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people) are exempt from both the 5% national threshold and the basic mandate clause.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The only party that has been able to benefit from this provision so far at the federal level is the South Schleswig Voters' Association, which represents the minorities of Danes and Frisians in Schleswig-Holstein, and succeeded in winning a seat in 1949, 2021, and 2025.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] If a member of parliament leaves the Bundestag during the current legislative term, either through resignation or death, another candidate from that party from the corresponding state takes their place.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Successful constituency candidates who did not receive a seat in the previous election due to the principle of second vote coverage are considered first, followed by the candidates on the respective state list.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] However, if the list is exhausted, the seat in question remains vacant for the remainder of the term.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] If the departing member was an independent constituency candidate, the seat also remains empty.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The latest federal election was held on Sunday, 23 February 2025, to elect the members of the 21st Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The executive bodies of the Bundestag are the Presidium and the Council of Elders.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Presidium consists of the President, the presiding officer, and several Vice Presidents.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The President and Vice Presidents are elected by the plenary of the Bundestag, whereby traditionally the largest fraction nominates the President and each fraction may nominate a vice president.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In addition to the members of the Presidium, the Council of Elders includes 23 other deputies who are delegated proportionally by the factions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The council is the coordination hub, determining the daily legislative agenda and assigning committee chairpersons based on Parliamentary group representation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The council also serves as an important forum for interparty negotiations on specific legislation and procedural issues.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Presidium is responsible for the routine administration of the Bundestag, including its clerical and research activities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag cannot be adjourned or prorogued during the current legislative term, but is always fully capable of acting and sets its own legislative calendar.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Normally, the Bundestag sits for at least twenty weeks per year, interrupted by non-sessional weeks, especially a long parliamentary summer recess, during which the MPs are present in their constituencies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The course of a session week is traditionally always the same: meetings of the parliamentary faction's internal committees take place on Monday and Tuesday mornings, and meetings in the faction-plenary on Tuesday afternoon.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] From Wednesday to Friday, plenary sessions and committee meetings take place in parallel (this is the reason why often very few members are present at plenary debates).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Committee meetings are interrupted on very important items on the agenda so that all MPs have the opportunity to be present in the plenary hall.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The highlights of the procedures include government statements by the Chancellor and the general debate at the beginning of the annual budget deliberations, during which there is a direct clash between the Chancellor and the opposition leader.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Independently of the usual procedure, the Bundestag can also convene for extraordinary sessions at any time.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] This must happen if one third of the MPs, the President of Germany or the Chancellor request it (Basic Law, Article 39.3).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The most important organisational structures within the Bundestag are 'factions' (*Fraktionen*; sing.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] A parliamentary faction must consist of at least 5% of all members of parliament.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Members of parliament from different parties may only join in a faction if those parties did not run against each other in any German state during the election.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Normally, all parties that surpassed the 5%-threshold build a faction of their own.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The CDU and CSU however, have always formed a joint faction, called CDU/CSU or Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] This is possible, as the CSU only runs in the state of Bavaria and the CDU only runs in the other 15 states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The size of a faction determines the extent of its representation on committees, the time slots allotted for speaking, the number of committee chairs it can hold, and its representation in executive bodies of the Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The factions, not the members, receive the bulk of government funding for legislative and administrative activities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The leadership of each *Fraktion* consists of a parliamentary party leader, several deputy leaders, and an executive committee.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The leadership's major responsibilities are to represent the *Fraktion*, enforce party discipline and orchestrate the party's parliamentary activities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The members of each *Fraktion* are distributed among working groups focused on specific policy-related topics such as social policy, economics, and foreign policy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The *Fraktion* meets every Tuesday afternoon in the weeks in which the Bundestag is in session to consider legislation before the Bundestag and formulate the party's position on it.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Parties that do not hold 5% of the Bundestag-seats may be granted the status of a *group* in the Bundestag; this is decided case by case, as the rules of procedure do not state a fixed number of seats for this.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] This status entails some privileges which are in general less than those of a faction.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Most of the legislative work in the Bundestag is the product of standing committees, which exist largely unchanged throughout one legislative period.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The number of committees approximates the number of federal ministries, and the titles of each are roughly similar (e.g., defense, agriculture, and labor).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] There are, as of the current nineteenth Bundestag, 24 standing committees.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The distribution of committee chairs and the membership of each committee reflect the relative strength of the various Parliamentary groups in the chamber.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] In the current nineteenth Bundestag, the CDU/CSU chaired ten committees, the SPD five, the AfD and the FDP three each, The Left and the Greens two each.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Members of the opposition party can chair a significant number of standing committees (e.g. the Budget Committee of the Bundestag was by tradition chaired by the biggest opposition party, until the 21st Bundestag, when Alternative for Germany was denied this post).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] These committees have either a small staff or no staff at all.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The members of Bundestag and the presidium are supported by the Bundestag Administration.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] It is headed by the Director, that reports to the President of the Bundestag.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag Administrations four departments are Parliament Service, Research, Information / Documentation and Central Affairs.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag Administration employs around 3,000 employees.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Also following the tradition of German diets, the German Bundestag can legally convene on any location, domestic and foreign.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Reichstag plenary chamber is not determined by law as the location of the assembly, making it a facility of convenience.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Bundestag's predecessor, the German Reichstag, convened in the Kroll Opera House in Berlin, after the Reichstag with its then wooden interior and walls burned down in the Reichstag fire.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] After World War II, the Bundestag did not have own facilities to call home and had to convene in the Bundeshaus in Bonn together with the Bundesrat.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] 1953, the plenary chambers in the Bundeshaus had to be expanded and the Bundestag assembled in a radio building in Cologne.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Until 1965, the Bundestag assembled in West Berlin for nine sessions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Seven sessions have been held in the Technische Universität Berlin and two sessions in Berlin's Congress Hall in Tiergarten.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The assemblies met severe protest from the communist side, the last session even interrupted by Soviet aircraft in supersonic low-altitude flight.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] 1971, the four occupying powers agreed to not accept Bundestag assemblies in West Berlin anymore.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled in the Old Waterworks Building in Bonn when the old plenary chamber had to get broken down, and in the new plenary chamber for only a few years after Germany's reunification.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The most distinctive assembly of the Bundestag outside its regular chambers was on 4 October 1990, the day after German reunification.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled inside the Reichstag building in Berlin for the first time after 57 years, and remote from its then-regular home in Bonn.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/bundestag] Soon after this most memorable assembly, the Bundestag decided to move from Bonn back to Berlin by a law which sets only the city of Berlin to be the home of the Bundestag, not the building.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] On 1 May 2017, *DRadio Wissen* was renamed *Deutschlandfunk Nova*, *Deutschlandradio Kultur* was renamed *Deutschlandfunk Kultur*.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] The three programs and the additional special event channel are all distributed terrestrially via Digital Audio Broadcasting (DAB+) on a nation-wide single frequency network (SFN) in VHF channel 5C.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] The coverage at the end of 2019 is for portable indoor reception 85% of the population and for mobile reception 96% of the area of Germany or 99% of the highways respectively.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] For an intermediate time the two programs Deutschlandfunk and Deutschlandfunk Kultur are still transmitted in analog way via FM with an average coverage of 64% of the area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] The switch over from analogue to digital started in 2015 with the switch-off of medium wave and long wave.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] In 2018/2019 first small-power FM transmitters were switched-off two.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] The aim is to further improve the digital terrestrial coverage of DAB+ and to reduce the analogue transmission step by step.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] For stationary reception the programs are also distributed via satellite on the transponder of ZDF.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] Of course the programs are streamed via the internet and available on relevant platforms.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] Beside the linear programs extensive non-linear content is available via audio-on-demand (podcast, mediathek and various platforms).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] Deutschlandradio is also very active in social media networks in order to make the content available to all public.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/deutschlandradio] The other shareholders are the Federal Republic of Germany (35%), the State of Berlin (20%) and RBB (5%).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The **European Union** (**EU**) is a political and economic union of 27 member states that are located primarily in Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The EU is often described as a *sui generis* political entity combining characteristics of both a federation and a confederation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Its cornerstone, the Customs Union, paved the way to establishing an internal single market based on standardised legal framework and legislation that applies in all member states in those matters, and only those matters, where the states have agreed to act as one.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] EU policies aim to ensure the free movement of people, goods, services and capital within the internal market; enact legislation in justice and home affairs; and maintain common policies on trade, agriculture, fisheries, and regional development.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Passport controls have been abolished for travel within the Schengen Area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The eurozone is a group composed of the 21 EU member states that have fully implemented the EU's economic and monetary union and use the euro currency.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Through the Common Foreign and Security Policy, the union has developed a role in external relations and defence.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] It maintains permanent diplomatic missions throughout the world and represents itself at the United Nations, the World Trade Organization, the G7 and the G20.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 2012, the EU was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The EU was established, along with its citizenship, when the Maastricht Treaty came into force in 1993, and was incorporated as an international legal juridical person upon entry into force of the Treaty of Lisbon in 2009.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] These increasingly amalgamated bodies grew, with their legal successor the EU, both in size through the accessions of a further 22 states from 1973 to 2013, and in power through acquisitions of policy areas.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 2020, the United Kingdom became the only member state to leave the EU; ten countries are aspiring or negotiating to join it.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Internationalism and visions of European unity had existed since well before the 19th century, but gained particularly as a reaction to World War I and its aftermath.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In this light the first advances for the idea of European integration were made.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] With large-scale war being waged in Europe once again in the 1930s and becoming World War II, the question of what to fight against and what for had to be agreed on.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] A first agreement was the Declaration of St James's Palace of 1941, when Europe's resistance gathered in London.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] This was expanded on by the 1941 Atlantic Charter, establishing the Allies and their common goals, inciting a new wave of global international institutions like the United Nations (founded 1945) or the Bretton Woods System (1944).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 1943 at the Moscow Conference and Tehran Conference, plans to establish joint institutions for a post-war world and Europe increasingly became a part of the agenda.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] This led to a decision at the Yalta Conference in 1944 to form a European Advisory Commission, later replaced by the Council of Foreign Ministers and the Allied Control Council, following the German surrender and the Potsdam Agreement in 1945.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] By the end of the war, European integration became seen as an antidote to the extreme nationalism that had caused the war.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] One month later, the French Union was installed by the new Fourth French Republic to direct the decolonisation of its colonies so that they would become parts of a European community.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] By 1947, a growing rift between the western Allied Powers and the Soviet Union became evident as a result of the rigged 1947 Polish legislative election, which constituted an open breach of the Yalta Agreement.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] March of that year saw two important developments.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] First was the signing of the Treaty of Dunkirk between France and the United Kingdom.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The treaty assured mutual assistance in the event of future military aggression against either nation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Though it officially named Germany as a threat, in reality the actual concern was for the Soviet Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] A few days later came the announcement of the Truman Doctrine which pledged American support for democracies to counter the Soviets.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Immediately following the February 1948 coup d'état by the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia, the London Six-Power Conference was held, resulting in the Soviet boycott of the Allied Control Council and its incapacitation, an event marking the beginning of the Cold War.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The year 1948 marked the beginning of the institutionalised modern European integration.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In March 1948 the Treaty of Brussels was signed, establishing the Western Union (WU), followed by the International Authority for the Ruhr.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Furthermore, the Organisation for European Economic Co-operation (OEEC), the predecessor of the OECD, was also founded in 1948 to manage the Marshall Plan, which led to the Soviets creating Comecon in response.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The ensuing Hague Congress of May 1948 was a pivotal moment in European integration, as it led to the creation of the European Movement International, the College of Europe, and most importantly to the foundation of the Council of Europe on 5 May 1949 (which is now Europe Day).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The Council of Europe was one of the first institutions to bring the sovereign states of (then only Western) Europe together, raising great hopes and fevered debates in the following two years for further European integration.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] It has since been a broad forum to further cooperation and shared issues, achieving for example the European Convention on Human Rights in 1950.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Essential for the actual birth of the institutions of the EU was the Schuman Declaration on 9 May 1950 (the day after the fifth Victory in Europe Day) and the decision by six nations (France, Belgium, Netherlands, Luxembourg, West Germany, and Italy) to follow Schuman and draft the Treaty of Paris.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] This treaty was created in 1952 the European Coal and Steel Community (ECSC), which was built on the International Authority for the Ruhr, installed by the Western Allies in 1949 to regulate the coal and steel industries of the Ruhr area in West Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Backed by the Marshall Plan with large funds coming from the United States since 1948, the ECSC became a milestone organisation, enabling European economic development and integration and being the origin of the main institutions of the EU such as the European Commission and Parliament.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The founding fathers of the European Union understood that coal and steel were the two industries essential for waging war, and believed that by tying their national industries together, a future war between their nations became much less likely.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 1954 the Modified Brussels Treaty transformed the Western Union into the Western European Union (WEU).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] West Germany eventually joined both the WEU and NATO in 1955, prompting the Soviet Union to form the Warsaw Pact in 1955 as an institutional framework for its military domination in the countries of Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Assessing the progress of European integration the Messina Conference was held in 1955, ordering the Spaak Report, which in 1956 recommended the next significant steps of European integration.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 1957, Belgium, France, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and West Germany signed the Treaty of Rome, which created the European Economic Community (EEC) and established a customs union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] They also signed another pact creating the European Atomic Energy Community (Euratom) for cooperation in developing nuclear power.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Although the EEC and Euratom were created separately from the ECSC, they shared the same courts and the Common Assembly.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The EEC was headed by Walter Hallstein (Hallstein Commission) and Euratom was headed by Louis Armand (Armand Commission) and then Étienne Hirsch (Hirsch Commission).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The OEEC was in turn reformed in 1961 into the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and its membership was extended to states outside of Europe, the United States and Canada.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] During the 1960s, tensions began to show, with France seeking to limit supranational power.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Nevertheless, in 1965 an agreement was reached, and on 1 July 1967 the Merger Treaty created a single set of institutions for the three communities, which were collectively referred to as the *European Communities*.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Jean Rey presided over the first merged commission (Rey Commission).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 1973, the communities were enlarged to include Denmark (including Greenland), Ireland, and the United Kingdom.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Norway had negotiated to join at the same time, but Norwegian voters rejected membership in a referendum.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The *Ostpolitik* and the ensuing détente led to establishment of a first truly pan-European body, the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe (CSCE), predecessor of the modern Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 1979, the first direct elections to the European Parliament were held.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 1985, Greenland left the Communities, following a dispute over fishing rights.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] During the same year, the Schengen Agreement paved the way for the creation of open borders without passport controls between most member states and some non-member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 1986, the Single European Act was signed.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 1990, after the fall of the Eastern Bloc, the former East Germany became part of the communities as part of a reunified Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The European Union was formally established when the Maastricht Treaty—whose main architects were Horst Köhler, Helmut Kohl and François Mitterrand—came into force on 1 November 1993.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The treaty also gave the name *European Community* to the EEC, even if it was referred to as such before the treaty.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] With further enlargement planned to include the former communist states of Central and Eastern Europe, as well as Cyprus and Malta, the Copenhagen criteria for candidate members to join the EU were agreed upon in June 1993.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The expansion of the EU introduced a new level of complexity and discord.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 1995, Austria, Finland, and Sweden joined the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 2002, euro banknotes and coins replaced national currencies in 12 of the member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Since then, the eurozone has increased to encompass 21 countries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The euro currency became the second-largest reserve currency in the world.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 2004, the EU saw its biggest enlargement to date when Cyprus, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, Poland, Slovakia, and Slovenia joined the union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 2007, Bulgaria and Romania became EU members.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Later that year, Slovenia adopted the euro, followed by Cyprus and Malta in 2008, Slovakia in 2009, Estonia in 2011, Latvia in 2014, Lithuania in 2015, and Croatia in 2023.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] On 1 December 2009, the Lisbon Treaty entered into force and reformed many aspects of the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 2012, the EU received the Nobel Peace Prize for having "contributed to the advancement of peace and reconciliation, democracy, and human rights in Europe".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In 2013, Croatia became the 28th EU member.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] From the beginning of the 2010s, the cohesion of the European Union has been tested by several issues, including the euro area crisis, 2015 European migrant crisis, and Brexit.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] A referendum in the UK on its membership of the European Union was held in 2016, with 51.9 per cent of participants voting to leave.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The early 2020s saw Denmark abolishing one of its three opt-outs and Croatia adopting the euro.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] After the economic crisis caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, the EU leaders agreed for the first time to create common debt to finance the European Recovery Program called Next Generation EU (NGEU).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] On 24 February 2022, after massing on the borders of Ukraine, the Russian Armed Forces undertook an attempt for a full-scale invasion of Ukraine.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The European Union imposed heavy sanctions on Russia and agreed on a pooled military aid package to Ukraine for lethal weapons funded via the European Peace Facility off-budget instrument.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] NGEU is a European Commission economic recovery package to support the EU member states to recover from the COVID-19 pandemic, in particular those that have been particularly hard hit.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] It is sometimes styled NextGenerationEU and Next Gen EU, and also called the European Union Recovery Instrument.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Agreed in principle by the European Council on 21 July 2020 and adopted on 14 December 2020, the instrument is worth €750 billion.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] NGEU will operate from 2021 to 2026, and will be tied to the regular 2021–2027 budget of the EU's Multiannual Financial Framework (MFF).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The comprehensive NGEU and MFF packages are projected to reach €1824.3 billion.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Preparing the EU for a new great enlargement is one of its political priorities, with the goal of achieving 35 member states by 2030.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Institutional and budgetary reforms are being discussed in order for the EU to be ready for the new members.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] In December 2025, it was leaked that the United States government would attempt to persuade "Austria, Hungary, Italy, and Poland" to depart the EU in a Brexit-type manner.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The following timeline outlines the legal inception of the European Union (EU)—the principal framework for this unification.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The EU inherited many of its present organisations, institutions, and responsibilities from the European Communities (EC), which were founded in the 1950s in the spirit of the Schuman Declaration.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Plans to establish a European Political Community (EPC) were shelved following the French failure to ratify the Treaty establishing the European Defence Community (EDC).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The EPC would have combined the ECSC and the EDC.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The European Communities obtained common institutions and a shared legal personality (i.e. ability to e.g. sign treaties in their own right).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The treaties of Maastricht and Rome form the EU's legal basis, and are also referred to as the Treaty on European Union (TEU) and the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU), respectively.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Between the EU's founding in 1993 and consolidation in 2009, the union consisted of three pillars, the first of which were the European Communities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The other two pillars consisted of additional areas of cooperation that had been added to the EU's remit.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] The consolidation meant that the EU inherited the European Communities' legal personality and that the pillar system was abolished, resulting in the EU framework as such covering all policy areas.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] Executive/legislative power in each area was instead determined by a distribution of competencies between EU institutions and member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p01] This distribution, as well as treaty provisions for policy areas in which unanimity is required and qualified majority voting is possible, reflects the depth of EU integration as well as the EU's partly supranational and partly intergovernmental nature.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Laws made by the EU institutions are passed in a variety of forms.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Generally speaking, they can be classified into two groups: those which come into force without the necessity for national implementation measures (regulations) and those which specifically require national implementation measures (directives).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] EU policy is in general promulgated by EU directives, which are then implemented in the domestic legislation of its member states, and EU regulations, which are immediately enforceable in all member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Lobbying at the EU level by special interest groups is regulated to try to balance the aspirations of private initiatives with public interest decision-making process.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Through successive enlargements, the EU and its predecessors have grown from the six founding states of the EEC to 27 members.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Countries accede to the union by becoming a party to the founding treaties, thereby subjecting themselves to the privileges and obligations of EU membership.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] This entails a partial delegation of sovereignty to the institutions in return for representation within those institutions, a practice often referred to as "pooling of sovereignty".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In some policies, there are several member states that ally with strategic partners within the union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Examples of such alliances include the Baltic Assembly, the Benelux Union, the Bucharest Nine, the Craiova Group, the EU Med Group, the Lublin Triangle, the New Hanseatic League, the Three Seas Initiative, the Visegrád Group, and the Weimar Triangle.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] To become a member, a country must meet the Copenhagen criteria, defined at the 1993 meeting of the European Council in Copenhagen.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] These require a stable democracy that respects human rights and the rule of law; a functioning market economy; and the acceptance of the obligations of membership, including EU law.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Evaluation of a country's fulfilment of the criteria is the responsibility of the European Council.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The relationships of the European microstates Andorra, Monaco, San Marino, and Vatican City include the use of the euro and other areas of co-operation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Subdivisions of member-states are based on the Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics (NUTS), a geocode standard for statistical purposes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The standard, adopted in 2003, is developed and regulated by the European Union, and thus only covers the member states of the EU in detail.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics is instrumental in the European Union's Structural Funds and Cohesion Fund delivery mechanisms and for locating the area where goods and services subject to European public procurement legislation are to be delivered.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] There are nine countries that are recognised as candidates for membership: Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, Moldova, Montenegro, North Macedonia, Serbia, Turkey, and Ukraine.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Norway, Switzerland and Iceland have submitted membership applications in the past, but subsequently froze or withdrew them.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Iceland is holding a referendum on resuming membership negotiations in August 2026.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Additionally Kosovo is officially recognised as a potential candidate, and has submitted a membership application.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty provides the basis for a member to leave the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Two territories have left the union: Greenland (an autonomous province of Denmark) withdrew in 1985; the United Kingdom formally invoked Article 50 of the Consolidated Treaty on European Union in 2017, and became the only sovereign state to leave when it withdrew from the EU in 2020.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Member states retain in principle all powers except those that they have agreed collectively to delegate to the union as a whole, though the exact delimitation has on occasions become a subject of scholarly or legal disputes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In certain fields, members have awarded exclusive competence and exclusive mandate to the union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] These are areas in which member states have entirely renounced their own capacity to enact legislation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In other areas, the EU and its member states share the competence to legislate.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] While both can legislate, the member states can only legislate to the extent to which the EU has not.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In other policy areas, the EU can only co-ordinate, support and supplement member state action but cannot enact legislation with the aim of harmonising national laws.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] That a particular policy area falls into a certain category of competence is not necessarily indicative of what legislative procedure is used for enacting legislation within that policy area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Different legislative procedures are used within the same category of competence, and even with the same policy area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Union has seven principal decision-making bodies, its institutions: the European Parliament, the European Council, the Council of the European Union, the European Commission, the Court of Justice of the European Union, the European Central Bank and the European Court of Auditors.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The monetary policy of the eurozone is determined by the European Central Bank.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The interpretation and the application of EU law and the treaties are ensured by the Court of Justice of the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU budget is scrutinised by the European Court of Auditors.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] There are also a number of ancillary bodies which advise the EU or operate in a specific area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The union's executive branch is organised as a directorial system, where the executive power is jointly exercised by several people.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The executive branch consists of the European Council and European Commission.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Council sets the broad political direction of the union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It convenes at least four times a year and comprises the president of the European Council (presently António Costa), the president of the European Commission and one representative per member state (either its head of state or head of government).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The high representative of the union for foreign affairs and security policy (presently Kaja Kallas) also takes part in its meetings.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Described by some as the union's "supreme political leadership", it is actively involved in the negotiation of treaty changes and defines the EU's policy agenda and strategies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Its leadership role involves solving disputes between member states and the institutions, and to resolving any political crises or disagreements over controversial issues and policies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It acts as a "collective head of state" and ratifies important documents (for example, international agreements and treaties).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Tasks for the president of the European Council are ensuring the external representation of the EU, driving consensus and resolving divergences among member states, both during meetings of the European Council and over the periods between them.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Council should not be mistaken for the Council of Europe, an international organisation independent of the EU and based in Strasbourg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Commission acts both as the EU's executive arm, responsible for the day-to-day running of the EU, and also the legislative initiator, with the sole power to propose laws for debate.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The commission is 'guardian of the Treaties' and is responsible for their efficient operation and policing.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It has 27 European commissioners for different areas of policy, one from each member state, though commissioners are bound to represent the interests of the EU as a whole rather than their home state.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The leader of the 27 is the president of the European Commission (presently Ursula von der Leyen for 2019–2024, reelected for the 2024–2029 term), proposed by the European Council, following and taking into account the result of the European elections, and is then elected by the European Parliament.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The President retains, as the leader responsible for the entire cabinet, the final say in accepting or rejecting a candidate submitted for a given portfolio by a member state, and oversees the commission's permanent civil service.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] After the President, the most prominent commissioner is the high representative of the union for foreign affairs and security policy, who is *ex-officio* a vice-president of the European Commission and is also chosen by the European Council.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The other 25 commissioners are subsequently appointed by the Council of the European Union in agreement with the nominated president.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The 27 commissioners as a single body are subject to approval (or otherwise) by a vote of the European Parliament.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] All commissioners are first nominated by the government of the respective member state.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The council, as it is now simply called (also called the Council of the European Union and the "Council of Ministers", its former title), forms one half of the EU's legislature.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It consists of a representative from each member state's government and meets in different compositions depending on the policy area being addressed.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Notwithstanding its different configurations, it is considered to be one single body.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In addition to the legislative functions, members of the council also have executive responsibilities, such as the development of a Common Foreign and Security Policy and the coordination of broad economic policies within the union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Presidency of the council rotates between member states, with each holding it for six months.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Beginning on 1 July 2025, the position is held by Denmark.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Parliament is one of three legislative institutions of the EU, which together with the Council of the European Union is tasked with amending and approving the European Commission's proposals.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] 705 members of the European Parliament (MEPs) are directly elected by EU citizens every five years on the basis of proportional representation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] MEPs are elected on a national basis and they sit according to political groups rather than their nationality.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Each country has a set number of seats and is divided into sub-national constituencies where this does not affect the proportional nature of the voting system.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In the ordinary legislative procedure, the European Commission proposes legislation, which requires the joint approval of the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union to pass.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] This process applies to nearly all areas, including the EU budget.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The parliament is the final body to approve or reject the proposed membership of the commission, and can attempt motions of censure on the commission by appeal to the Court of Justice.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The president of the European Parliament carries out the role of speaker in Parliament and represents it externally.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The president and vice-presidents are elected by MEPs every two and a half years.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The judicial branch of the European Union is formally called the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU) and consists of two courts: the Court of Justice and the General Court.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Court of Justice is the supreme court of the European Union in matters of European Union law.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] As a part of the CJEU, it is tasked with interpreting EU law and ensuring its uniform application across all EU member states under Article 263 of the Treaty of the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Court was established in 1952, and is based in Luxembourg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It is composed of one judge per member state – currently 27 – although it normally hears cases in panels of three, five or fifteen judges.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Court has been led by president Koen Lenaerts since 2015.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The CJEU is the highest court of the European Union in matters of Union law.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Its case-law provides that EU law has supremacy over any national law that is inconsistent with EU law.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It is not possible to appeal against the decisions of national courts in the CJEU, but rather national courts refer questions of EU law to the CJEU (a preliminary reference).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] However, it is ultimately for the national court to apply the resulting interpretation (the preliminary ruling) to the facts of any given case.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Although, only courts of final appeal are bound to refer a question of EU law when one is addressed.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The treaties give the CJEU the power for consistent application of EU law across the EU as a whole.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The court also acts as an administrative and constitutional court between the other EU institutions and the Member States and can annul or invalidate unlawful acts of EU institutions, bodies, offices and agencies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The General Court is a constituent court of the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It hears actions taken against the institutions of the European Union by individuals and member states, although certain matters are reserved for the Court of Justice.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Decisions of the General Court can be appealed to the Court of Justice, but only on a point of law.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Prior to the coming into force of the Lisbon Treaty on 1 December 2009, it was known as the Court of First Instance.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Since the amendments to the Statute of the CJEU in October 2024, the Court of Justice shares its jurisdiction over references for a preliminary ruling with the General Court.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Central Bank (ECB) is one of the institutions of the monetary branch of the European Union, the prime component of the Eurosystem and the European System of Central Banks.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It is one of the world's most important central banks.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The ECB Governing Council makes monetary policy for the eurozone and the European Union, administers the foreign exchange reserves of EU member states, engages in foreign exchange operations, and defines the intermediate monetary objectives and key interest rate of the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The ECB Executive Board enforces the policies and decisions of the Governing Council, and may direct the national central banks when doing so.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The ECB has the exclusive right to authorise the issuance of euro banknotes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Member states can issue euro coins, but the volume must be approved by the ECB beforehand.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The bank also operates the T2 (RTGS) payments system.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European System of Central Banks (ESCB) consists of the ECB and the national central banks (NCBs) of all 27 member states of the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The ESCB is not the monetary authority of the eurozone, because not all EU member states have joined the euro.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The ESCB's objective is price stability throughout the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Secondarily, the ESCB's goal is to improve monetary and financial cooperation between the Eurosystem and member states outside the eurozone.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Court of Auditors (ECA) is the auditory branch of the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It was established in 1975 in Luxembourg in order to improve EU financial management.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It has 27 members (1 from each EU member-state) supported by approximately 800 civil servants.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Personnel Selection Office (EPSO) is the EU's civil service recruitment body and operates its selection of candidates via generalist and specialist competitions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Each institution is then able to recruit staff from among the pool of candidates selected by EPSO.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] On average, EPSO receives around 60,000–70,000 applications a year with around 1,500–2,000 candidates recruited by the European Union institutions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Ombudsman is the ombudsman branch of the European Union that holds the institutions, bodies and agencies of the EU to account, and promotes good administration.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Ombudsman helps people, businesses and organisations facing problems with the EU administration by investigating complaints, as well as by proactively looking into broader systemic issues.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The current Ombudsman is Teresa Anjinho.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Public Prosecutor's Office (EPPO) is the prosecutory branch of the union with juridical personality, established under the Treaty of Lisbon between 23 of the 27 states of the EU following the method of enhanced cooperation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Union’s public ethics system is highly fragmented, with various bespoke public integrity regimes coexisting under EU law, each possessing its own ethics principles and obligations.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] EU ethics standards are scattered across multiple legal sources, ranging from the EU Treaties and institutional Rules of Procedure to Codes of Conduct and the EU Staff Regulations.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] While public ethics instruments exist in almost all EU institutions, there is less evidence that ethics constitutes an integrated feature of day-to-day EU policymaking, a concept defined by scholars as "ethical governance".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Historically, the system's enforcement mechanisms have faced severe structural limitations, notably high fragmentation, limited independence, and weak sanctioning powers.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Furthermore, virtually all EU institutions have traditionally entrusted the respect of these rules to themselves through internal self-assessment mechanisms rather than independent external oversight.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The 2022 Qatargate influence-buying scandal served as a critical juncture that accelerated the push for systemic reform across the institutions, as public perception of the transparency and independence of EU institutions vis-à-vis private interests remained poor.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In 2021, the European Parliament had initially proposed the creation of a strong, independent ethics body equipped with its own investigative and enforcement powers.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Instead, the main EU institutions concluded an agreement, formally signed in May 2024, to establish a comparatively constrained Interinstitutional Body for Ethical Standards (IBES).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The core task of this new entity is the development of "common minimum standards" for the conduct of the political members of the participating institutions, strictly excluding the EU civil service staff.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The new body adopts these minimum standards by consensus and is assisted by five independent experts.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Court of Justice of the EU (ECJ) participates only as an observer to preserve its judicial impartiality.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Interinstitutional EU Ethics Body (or Interinstitutional Body for Ethical Standards; IBES) faces specific legal and constitutional constraints.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Functioning through the "contractual" conjunction of each participating institution, the body operates primarily as a formal mechanism for coordination rather than a centralized enforcement agency.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Curiously the body is not based on the Treaty legal basis for IIAs (Inter Institutional Agreements) (Article 295 TFEU), as this article only refers to the three main EU institutions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It cannot take over decision-making powers for individual disciplinary cases..
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Consequently, it does not replace existing ethical authorities but merely aims at complementing them, and its creation explicitly does not encroach upon the investigative competences of the European Anti-Fraud Office (OLAF) or the European Ombudsman.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Ombudsman continues to play a parallel role in assessing ethical breaches and conflicts of interests under the broader concept of "maladministration", which goes beyond strict illegality.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Academic evaluations and civil society groups generally characterize the creation of the IBES as an example of "incremental change" rather than comprehensive reform.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Civil society organizations, such as Transparency International, have criticized the final agreement as "toothless" due to its inability to independently investigate or sanction the EU institutions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Similarly, legal scholars point out that the body lacks investigative powers and the capacity to apply ethical standards to concrete individual cases.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Nevertheless, because the body requires each participating institution to conduct a public, written self-assessment of its internal rules, experts suggest that the ensuing public scrutiny and institutional peer pressure may induce institutions to align their standards more closely over time.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Union had an agreed budget of €170.6 billion in 2022.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU had a long-term budget of €1,082.5 billion for the period 2014–2020, representing 1.02% of the EU-28's GNI.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In 1960, the budget of the European Community was 0.03 per cent of GDP.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Of this, €54bn subsidised agriculture enterprise, €42bn was spent on transport, building and the environment, €16bn on education and research, €13bn on welfare, €20bn on foreign and defence policy, €2bn in finance, €2bn in energy, €1.5bn in communications, and €13bn in administration.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In November 2020, two members of the union, Hungary and Poland, blocked approval to the EU's budget at a meeting in the Committee of Permanent Representatives (Coreper), citing a proposal that linked funding with adherence to the rule of law.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The budget included a COVID-19 recovery fund of €750 billion.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The budget was finally approved by 12 December when Hungary and Poland withdrew their vetoes after further negotiations in the council and the European Council.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Bodies combatting fraud have also been established, including the European Anti-fraud Office and the European Public Prosecutor's Office.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The latter is a decentralised independent body of the European Union (EU), established under the Treaty of Lisbon between 22 of the 27 states of the EU following the method of enhanced cooperation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Public Prosecutor's Office investigate and prosecute fraud against the budget of the European Union and other crimes against the EU's financial interests including fraud concerning EU funds of over €10,000 and cross-border VAT fraud cases involving damages above €10 million.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Constitutionally, the EU bears some resemblance to both a confederation and a federation, but has not formally defined itself as either.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] (It does not have a formal constitution: its status is defined by the Treaty of European Union and the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It is more integrated than a traditional confederation of states because the general level of government widely employs qualified majority voting in some decision-making among the member states, rather than relying exclusively on unanimity.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU is less integrated than a federal state because it is not a state in its own right: sovereignty continues to flow 'from the bottom up', from the several peoples of the separate member states, rather than from a single undifferentiated whole.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In addition, the principle of subsidiarity requires that only those matters that need to be determined collectively are so determined.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Under the principle of supremacy, national courts are required to enforce the treaties that their member states have ratified, even if doing so requires them to ignore conflicting national law, and (within limits) even constitutional provisions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The direct effect and supremacy doctrines were not explicitly set out in the European Treaties but were developed by the Court of Justice itself over the 1960s, apparently under the influence of its then most influential judge, Frenchman Robert Lecourt.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The question whether the secondary law enacted by the EU has a comparable status in relation to national legislation, has been a matter of debate among legal scholars.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Union is based on a series of treaties.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] These first established the European Community and the EU, and then made amendments to those founding treaties.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] These are power-giving treaties which set broad policy goals and establish institutions with the necessary legal powers to implement those goals.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] These legal powers include the ability to enact legislation which can directly affect all member states and their inhabitants.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU has legal personality, with the right to sign agreements and international treaties.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The main legal acts of the European Union come in three forms: regulations, directives, and decisions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Regulations become law in all member states the moment they come into force, without the requirement for any implementing measures, and automatically override conflicting domestic provisions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Directives require member states to achieve a certain result while leaving them discretion as to how to achieve the result.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The details of how they are to be implemented are left to member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] When the time limit for implementing directives passes, they may, under certain conditions, have direct effect in national law against member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Decisions offer an alternative to the two above modes of legislation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] They are legal acts which only apply to specified individuals, companies or a particular member state.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] They are most often used in competition law, or on rulings on State Aid, but are also frequently used for procedural or administrative matters within the institutions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Regulations, directives, and decisions are of equal legal value and apply without any formal hierarchy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Foreign policy co-operation between member states dates from the establishment of the community in 1957, when member states negotiated as a bloc in international trade negotiations under the EU's common commercial policy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Steps for more wide-ranging co-ordination in foreign relations began in 1970 with the establishment of European Political Cooperation which created an informal consultation process between member states with the aim of forming common foreign policies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In 1987 the European Political Cooperation was introduced on a formal basis by the Single European Act.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] EPC was renamed as the Common Foreign and Security Policy (CFSP) by the Maastricht Treaty.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The stated aims of the CFSP are to promote both the EU's own interests and those of the international community as a whole, including the furtherance of international co-operation, respect for human rights, democracy, and the rule of law.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The CFSP requires unanimity among the member states on the appropriate policy to follow on any particular issue.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The unanimity and difficult issues treated under the CFSP sometimes lead to disagreements, such as those which occurred over the war in Iraq.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The high representative heads up the European External Action Service (EEAS), a unique EU department that has been officially implemented and operational since 1 December 2010 on the occasion of the first anniversary of the entry into force of the Treaty of Lisbon.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EEAS serves as a foreign ministry and diplomatic corps for the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Besides the emerging international policy of the European Union, the international influence of the EU is also felt through enlargement.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The perceived benefits of becoming a member of the EU act as an incentive for both political and economic reform in states wishing to fulfil the EU's accession criteria, and are considered an important factor contributing to the reform of European formerly Communist countries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] This influence on the internal affairs of other countries is generally referred to as "soft power", as opposed to military "hard power".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Commission's Humanitarian Aid and Civil Protection department, or "ECHO", provides humanitarian aid from the EU to developing countries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In 2012, its budget amounted to €874 million, 51 per cent of the budget went to Africa and 20 per cent to Asia, Latin America, the Caribbean and Pacific, and 20 per cent to the Middle East and Mediterranean.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Humanitarian aid is financed directly by the budget (70 per cent) as part of the financial instruments for external action and also by the European Development Fund (30 per cent).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU's external action financing is divided into geographic instruments and thematic instruments.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In 2016, the average among EU countries was 0.4 per cent and five had met or exceeded the 0.7 per cent target: Denmark, Germany, Luxembourg, Sweden, and the United Kingdom.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Union uses foreign relations instruments like the European Neighbourhood Policy which seeks to tie those countries to the east and south of the European territory of the EU to the union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] These countries, primarily developing countries, include some who seek to one day become either a member state of the European Union, or more closely integrated with the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU offers financial assistance to countries within the European Neighbourhood, so long as they meet the strict conditions of government reform, economic reform and other issues surrounding positive transformation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] This process is normally underpinned by an Action Plan, as agreed by both Brussels and the target country.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] There is also the worldwide European Union Global Strategy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] International recognition of sustainable development as a key element is growing steadily.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Other key global agreements are the Paris Agreement and the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development (United Nations, 2015).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The SDGs recognise that all countries must stimulate action in the following key areas – people, planet, prosperity, peace and partnership – in order to tackle the global challenges that are crucial for the survival of humanity.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] EU development action is based on the European Consensus on Development, which was endorsed on 20 December 2005 by EU Member States, the council, the European Parliament and the commission.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] It is applied from the principles of capability approach and rights-based approach to development.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Funding is provided by the Instrument for Pre-Accession Assistance and the Global Europe programmes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Partnership and cooperation agreements are bilateral agreements with non-member nations.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The predecessors of the European Union were not devised as a military alliance because NATO was largely seen as appropriate and sufficient for defence purposes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Twenty-three EU members are members of NATO while the remaining member states follow policies of neutrality.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Western European Union, a military alliance with a mutual defence clause, closed in 2011 as its role had been transferred to the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] To that end, a number of efforts were made to increase the EU's military capability, notably the Helsinki Headline Goal process.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] After much discussion, the most concrete result was the EU Battlegroups initiative, each of which is planned to be able to deploy quickly about 1500 personnel.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Since the withdrawal of the United Kingdom, France is the only member officially recognised as a nuclear weapon state and the sole holder of a permanent seat on the United Nations Security Council.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] France and Italy are also the only EU countries that have power projection capabilities outside of Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Italy, Germany, the Netherlands and Belgium participate in NATO nuclear sharing.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Most EU member states opposed the Nuclear Weapon Ban Treaty.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] EU forces have been deployed on peacekeeping missions from middle and northern Africa to the western Balkans and western Asia.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] EU military operations are supported by a number of bodies, including the European Defence Agency, European Union Satellite Centre and the European Union Military Staff.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Union Military Staff is under the authority of the High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy and the Political and Security Committee.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In an EU consisting of 27 members, substantial security and defence co-operation is increasingly relying on collaboration among all member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Border and Coast Guard Agency (Frontex) is an agency of the EU aiming to detect and stop illegal immigration, human trafficking and terrorist infiltration.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU also operates the European Travel Information and Authorisation System, the Entry/Exit System, the Schengen Information System, the Visa Information System and the Common European Asylum System which provide common databases for police and immigration authorities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The impetus for the development of this co-operation was the advent of open borders in the Schengen Area and the associated cross-border crime.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU's member states cover an area of 4,233,262 square kilometres (1,634,472 sq mi), and therefore a large part of the European continent.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU's highest peak is Mont Blanc in the Graian Alps, 4,810.45 metres (15,782 ft) above sea level.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The lowest points in the EU are Lammefjorden, Denmark, and Zuidplaspolder, Netherlands, at 7 m (23 ft) below sea level.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The landscape, climate, and economy of the EU are influenced by its coastline, which is 65,993 kilometres (41,006 mi) long.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In addition to national territories in Europe, there are 32 special territories of members of the European Economic Area, not all of which are part of the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The largest by area is Greenland, which is not part of the EU but whose citizens are EU citizens, while the largest by population are the Canary Islands off Africa, which are part of the EU and the Schengen area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] French Guiana in South America is part of the EU and the eurozone, as is Mayotte, north of Madagascar.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The climate of the European Union is of a temperate, continental nature, with a maritime climate prevailing on the western coasts and a mediterranean climate in the south.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The climate is strongly conditioned by the Gulf Stream, which warms the western region to levels unattainable at similar latitudes on other continents.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Western Europe is oceanic, while eastern Europe is continental and dry.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Four seasons occur in western Europe, while southern Europe experiences a wet season and a dry season.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Southern Europe is hot and dry during the summer months.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The heaviest precipitation occurs downwind of water bodies due to the prevailing westerlies, with higher amounts also seen in the Alps.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In 1957, when the European Economic Community was founded, it had no environmental policy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Over the past 50 years, an increasingly dense network of legislation has been created, extending to all areas of environmental protection, including air pollution, water quality, waste management, nature conservation, and the control of chemicals, industrial hazards, and biotechnology.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] According to the Institute for European Environmental Policy, environmental law comprises over 500 Directives, Regulations and Decisions, making environmental policy a core area of European politics.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] European policy-makers originally increased the EU's capacity to act on environmental issues by defining it as a trade problem.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Trade barriers and competitive distortions in the Common Market could emerge due to the different environmental standards in each member state.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In subsequent years, the environment became a formal policy area, with its own policy actors, principles and procedures.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The legal basis for EU environmental policy was established with the introduction of the Single European Act in 1987.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Initially, EU environmental policy focused on Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] More recently, the EU has demonstrated leadership in global environmental governance, e.g. the role of the EU in securing the ratification and coming into force of the Kyoto Protocol despite opposition from the United States.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] This international dimension is reflected in the EU's Sixth Environmental Action Programme, which recognises that its objectives can only be achieved if key international agreements are actively supported and properly implemented both at EU level and worldwide.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Lisbon Treaty further strengthened the leadership ambitions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] EU law has played a significant role in improving habitat and species protection in Europe, as well as contributing to improvements in air and water quality and waste management.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Mitigating climate change is one of the top priorities of EU environmental policy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In 2007, member states agreed that, in the future, 20 per cent of the energy used across the EU must be renewable, and carbon dioxide emissions have to be lower in 2020 by at least 20 per cent compared to 1990 levels.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In 2017, the EU emitted 9.1 per cent of global greenhouse-gas emissions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Union claims that already in 2018, its GHG emissions were 23% lower than in 1990.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The EU has adopted an emissions trading system to incorporate carbon emissions into the economy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The European Green Capital is an annual award given to cities that focuses on the environment, energy efficiency, and quality of life in urban areas to create smart city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In the 2019 elections to the European Parliament, the green parties increased their power, possibly because of the rise of post materialist values.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Proposals to reach a zero carbon economy in the European Union by 2050 were suggested in 2018–2019.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Almost all member states supported that goal at an EU summit in June 2019.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, and Poland disagreed.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In June 2021, the European Union passed a European Climate Law with targets of 55% GHG emissions reduction by 2030 and carbon neutrality by 2050.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] Also in the same year, the European Union and the United States pledged to cut methane emissions by 30% by 2030.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] The pledge is considered as a big achievement for climate change mitigation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] A research report from November 2024 declared that the Czech Republic is the EU's most toxic country in Europe for car emissions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] In 2025, The European Union together with China, Brazil and others, joined the Global carbon market coalition.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p02] According to some calculations, a global carbon market can speed up emission reduction seven-fold.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The gross domestic product (GDP), a measure of economic activity, of EU member states was US$16.64 trillion in 2022, around 16.6 per cent of the world GDP.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] There is a significant variation in GDP per capita between and within individual EU states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The difference between the richest and poorest regions (281 NUTS-2 regions of the Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics) ranged, in 2017, from 31 per cent (Severozapaden, Bulgaria) of the EU28 average (€30,000) to 253 per cent (Luxembourg), or from €4,600 to €92,600.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] EU member states own the estimated third largest after the United States (US$140 trillion) and China (US$84 trillion) net wealth in the world, equal to around one sixth (US$76 trillion) of the US$454 trillion global wealth.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Of the top 500 largest corporations in the world measured by revenue in 2024, 90 had their headquarters in the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 2016, unemployment in the EU stood at 8.9 per cent while inflation was at 2.2 per cent, and the account balance at −0.9 per cent of GDP.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The average annual net earnings in the European Union was around €25,000 in 2021.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The euro is the official currency in 21 member states of the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The creation of a European single currency became an official objective of the European Economic Community in 1969.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 1992, having negotiated the structure and procedures of a currency union, the member states signed the Maastricht Treaty and were legally bound to fulfil the agreed-on rules including the convergence criteria if they wanted to join the monetary union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The states wanting to participate had first to join the European Exchange Rate Mechanism.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Free movement of capital is intended to permit movement of investments such as property purchases and buying of shares between countries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Until the drive towards economic and monetary union the development of the capital provisions had been slow.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Post-Maastricht there has been a rapidly developing corpus of ECJ judgements regarding this initially neglected freedom.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The free movement of capital is unique insofar as it is granted equally to non-member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European System of Financial Supervision is an institutional architecture of the EU's framework of financial supervision composed by three authorities: the European Banking Authority, the European Insurance and Occupational Pensions Authority and the European Securities and Markets Authority.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] To complement this framework, there is also a European Systemic Risk Board under the responsibility of the central bank.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The aim of this financial control system is to ensure the economic stability of the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 1999, the currency union started to materialise through introducing a common accounting (virtual) currency in eleven of the member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 2002, it was turned into a fully-fledged conventible currency, when euro notes and coins were issued, while the phaseout of national currencies in the eurozone (consisting by then of 12 member states) was initiated.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The eurozone (constituted by the EU member states which have adopted the euro) has since grown to 20 countries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The 20 EU member states known collectively as the eurozone have fully implemented the currency union by superseding their national currencies with the euro.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The currency union represents 345 million EU citizens.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The euro is the second largest reserve currency as well as the second most traded currency in the world after the United States dollar.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The euro, and the monetary policies of those who have adopted it in agreement with the EU, are under the control of the ECB.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The ECB is the central bank for the eurozone, and thus controls monetary policy in that area with an agenda to maintain price stability.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It is at the centre of the Eurosystem, which comprehends all the eurozone national central banks.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The ECB is also the central institution of the Banking Union established within the eurozone, as the hub of European Banking Supervision.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] There is also a Single Resolution Mechanism in case of a bank default.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] As a political entity, the European Union is represented in the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Two of the original core objectives of the European Economic Community were the development of a common market, subsequently becoming a single market, and a customs union between its member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The single market involves the free circulation of goods, capital, people, and services within the EU, The free movement of services and of establishment allows self-employed persons to move between member states to provide services on a temporary or permanent basis.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] While services account for 60 per cent to 70 per cent of GDP, legislation in the area is not as developed as in other areas.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] This lacuna has been addressed by the Services in the Internal Market Directive 2006 which aims to liberalise the cross border provision of services.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] According to the treaty the provision of services is a residual freedom that only applies if no other freedom is being exercised.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The customs union involves the application of a common external tariff on all goods entering the market.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Once goods have been admitted into the market they cannot be subjected to customs duties, discriminatory taxes or import quotas, as they travel internally.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The non-EU member states of Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland participate in the single market but not in the customs union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Half the trade in the EU is covered by legislation harmonised by the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Union Association Agreement does something similar for a much larger range of countries, partly as a so-called soft approach ('a carrot instead of a stick') to influence the politics in those countries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Union represents all its members at the World Trade Organization (WTO), and acts on behalf of member states in any disputes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] When the EU negotiates trade related agreement outside the WTO framework, the subsequent agreement must be approved by each individual EU member state government.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU operates a competition policy intended to ensure undistorted competition within the single market.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 2001 the commission for the first time prevented a merger between two companies based in the United States (General Electric and Honeywell) which had already been approved by their national authority.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Another high-profile case, against Microsoft, resulted in the commission fining Microsoft over €777 million following nine years of legal action.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Union has concluded free trade agreements (FTAs) and other agreements with a trade component with many countries worldwide and is negotiating with many others.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Union's services trade surplus rose from $16 billion in 2000 to more than $250 billion in 2018.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 2020, in part due to the COVID-19 pandemic, China became the EU's largest trading partner, displacing the United States.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Union is the largest exporter in the world and in 2008 was the largest importer of goods and services.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Internal trade between the member states is aided by the removal of barriers to trade such as tariffs and border controls.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In the eurozone, trade is helped by not having any currency differences to deal with amongst most members.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Externally, the EU's free-trade agreement with Japan is perhaps its most notable one.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU-Japan Economic Partnership Agreement was officially signed on 17 July 2018, becoming the world's largest bilateral free trade deal when it went into effect on 1 February 2019, creating an open trade zone covering nearly one-third of global GDP.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The total energy supply of the EU was 59 billion GJ in 2019, about 10.2 per cent of the world total.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Approximately three fifths of the energy available in the EU came from imports (mostly of fossil fuels).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Renewable energy contributed 18.1 per cent of the EU's total energy supply in 2019, and 11.1 per cent of the final energy consumption.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU has had legislative power in the area of energy policy for most of its existence; this has its roots in the original European Coal and Steel Community.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The introduction of a mandatory and comprehensive European energy policy was approved at the meeting of the European Council in October 2005, and the first draft policy was published in January 2007.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 2007, EU countries as a whole imported 82 per cent of their oil, 57 per cent of their natural gas and 97.48 per cent of their uranium demands.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The three largest suppliers of natural gas to the European Union are Russia, Norway and Algeria, that amounted for about three quarters of the imports in 2019.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] There is a strong dependence on Russian energy that the EU has been attempting to reduce.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In May 2022, it was reported that the European Union was preparing another sanction against Russia over its invasion of Ukraine.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It is expected to target Russian oil, Russian and Belarusian banks, as well as individuals and companies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] According to an article by Reuters, two diplomats stated that the European Union may impose a ban on imports of Russian oil by the end of 2022.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Also in May 2022, the European Commission published the RePowerEU initiative, a €300 billion plan outlining the path towards the end of EU dependence on Russian fossil fuels by 2030 and the acceleration on the clean energy transition.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Union manages cross-border road, railway, airport and water infrastructure through the Trans-European Transport Network (TEN-T), created in 1990, and the Trans-European Combined Transport network.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] TEN-T comprises two network layers: the Core Network, which is to be completed by 2030; and the Comprehensive Network, which is to be completed by 2050.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Road transportation was organised under the TEN-T by the Trans-European road network.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Bundesautobahn 7 is the longest national motorway in the EU at 963 km (598 mi).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Maritime transportation is organised under the TEN-T by the Trans-European Inland Waterway network, and the Trans-European Seaport network.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] European seaports are categorised as international, community, or regional.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Port of Rotterdam is the busiest in the EU, and the world's largest seaport outside of East Asia, located in and near the city of Rotterdam, in the province of South Holland in the Netherlands.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Maritime Safety Agency (EMSA), founded in 2002 in Lisbon, Portugal, is charged with reducing the risk of maritime accidents, marine pollution from ships and the loss of human lives at sea by helping to enforce the pertinent EU legislation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Air transportation is organised under the TEN-T by the Trans-European Airport network.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] European airports are categorised as international, community, or regional.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Charles de Gaulle Airport is the busiest in the EU, located in and near the city of Paris, in France.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Common Aviation Area (ECAA) is a single market in aviation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] ECAA agreements were signed on 5 May 2006 in Salzburg, Austria between the EU and some third countries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The ECAA liberalises the air transport industry by allowing any company from any ECAA member state to fly between any ECAA member states airports, thereby allowing a "foreign" airline to provide domestic flights.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Civil aviation safety is under the responsibility of the European Union Aviation Safety Agency (EASA).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It carries out certification, regulation and standardisation and also performs investigation and monitoring.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The idea of a European-level aviation safety authority goes back to 1996, but the agency was only legally established in 2002, and began operating in 2003.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Rail transportation is organised under the TEN-T by the Trans-European Rail network, made up of the high-speed rail network and the conventional rail network.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Gare du Nord railway station is the busiest in the EU, located in and near the city of Paris, in France.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Rail transport in Europe is being synchronised with the European Rail Traffic Management System (ERTMS) with the goal of greatly enhancing safety, increase efficiency of train transports and enhance cross-border interoperability.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] This is done by replacing former national signalling equipment and operational procedures with a single new Europe-wide standard for train control and command systems.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] This system is conducted by the European Union Agency for Railways (ERA).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Schengen Area is an area comprising 29 European countries that have officially abolished all passport and all other types of border control at their mutual borders.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Being an element within the wider area of freedom, security and justice policy of the EU, it mostly functions as a single jurisdiction under a common visa policy for international travel purposes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The area is named after the 1985 Schengen Agreement and the 1990 Schengen Convention, both signed in Schengen, Luxembourg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Of the 27 EU member states, 25 participate in the Schengen Area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Of the EU members that are not part of the Schengen Area, one—Cyprus—is legally obligated to join the area in the future; Ireland maintains an opt-out, and instead operates its own visa policy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The four European Free Trade Association (EFTA) member states, Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway, and Switzerland, are not members of the EU, but have signed agreements in association with the Schengen Agreement.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Mobile communication roaming charges are abolished throughout the EU, Iceland, Liechtenstein and Norway.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] This was the first common political framework for space activities established by the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Each member state has pursued to some extent their own national space policy, though often co-ordinating through the ESA.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Galileo is a global navigation satellite system (GNSS) that went live in 2016, created by the EU through the ESA, operated by the EUSPA, with two ground operations centres in Fucino, Italy, and Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The €10 billion project is named after the Italian astronomer Galileo Galilei.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] One of the aims of Galileo is to provide an independent high-precision positioning system so European political and military authorities do not have to rely on the US GPS, or the Russian GLONASS systems, which could be disabled or degraded by their operators at any time.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Geostationary Navigation Overlay Service (EGNOS) is a satellite-based augmentation system (SBAS) developed by the ESA and EUROCONTROL.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Currently, it supplements the GPS by reporting on the reliability and accuracy of their positioning data and sending out corrections.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The system will supplement Galileo in a future version.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Copernicus Programme is the EU's Earth observation programme coordinated and managed by EUSPA in partnership with ESA.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) is the agricultural policy of the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It implements a system of agricultural subsidies and other programmes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It was introduced in 1962 and has since then undergone several changes to reduce the EEC budget cost (from 73% in 1985 to 37% in 2017) and consider rural development in its aims.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It has, however, been criticised on the grounds of its cost and its environmental and humanitarian effects.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Likewise, the Common Fisheries Policy (CFP) is the fisheries policy of the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It sets quotas for which member states are allowed to catch each type of fish, as well as encouraging the fishing industry by various market interventions and fishing subsidies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It was introduced in 2009 with the Treaty of Lisbon, which formally enshrined fisheries conservation policy as one of the handful of "exclusive competences" reserved for the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The free movement of persons means that EU citizens can move freely between member states to live, work, study or retire in another country.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] This required the lowering of administrative formalities and recognition of professional qualifications of other states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU seasonally adjusted unemployment rate was 6.7 per cent in September 2018.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The euro area unemployment rate was 8.1 per cent.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Among the member states, the lowest unemployment rates were recorded in the Czech Republic (2.3 per cent), Germany and Poland (both 3.4 per cent), and the highest in Spain (10.61 per cent in 2024) and Greece (9.6 per cent in November 2024).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Union has long sought to mitigate the effects of free markets by protecting workers' rights and preventing social and environmental dumping.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] To this end, it has adopted laws establishing minimum employment and environmental standards.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] These included the Working Time Directive and the Environmental Impact Assessment Directive.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Directive about Minimum Wage, which looks to lift minimum wages and strengthen collective bargaining was approved by the European Parliament in September 2022.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The five European Structural and Investment Funds are supporting the development of the EU regions, primarily the underdeveloped ones, located mostly in the states of central and southern Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Another fund (the Instrument for Pre-Accession Assistance) provides support for candidate members to transform their country to conform to the EU's standard.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Demographic transition to a society of ageing population, low fertility-rates and depopulation of non-metropolitan regions is tackled within this policies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The population of the EU in 2024 was about 450 million people, corresponding to 5.8 per cent of the world population.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The population density across the EU was 106 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is more than the world average.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It is highest in areas in central and western Europe, sometimes referred to as the "blue banana", while Sweden and Finland in the north are much more sparsely populated.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The total population of the EU has been slightly decreasing for several years, contracting by 0.04 per cent in 2021.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] This is due to a low birth rate of about 1.5 children per woman, less than the world average of 2.3.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In total, 4.1 million babies were born in the EU in 2021.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Of the people residing in the EU, 5.3 per cent are not EU citizens.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] There were 31 non-EU citizenships that each accounted for at least 1 per cent of non-EU citizens living in the EU, of which the largest were Moroccan, Turkish, Syrian and Chinese.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Around 1.9 million people immigrated to one of the EU member states from a non-EU country during 2020, and a total of 956,000 people emigrated from a member state to go to a non-EU country during the same year.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] More than two thirds (68.2%) of EU inhabitants lived in urban areas in 2020, which is slightly less than the world average.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Cities are largely spread out across the EU with a large grouping in and around the Benelux.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU contains about 40 urban areas with populations of over 1 million.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] With a population of over 13 million, Paris is the largest metropolitan area and the only megacity in the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Paris is followed by Madrid, Barcelona, Berlin, the Ruhr, Milan, and Rome, all with a metropolitan population of over 4 million.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU has 24 official languages: Bulgarian, Croatian, Czech, Danish, Dutch, English, Estonian, Finnish, French, German, Greek, Hungarian, Italian, Irish, Latvian, Lithuanian, Maltese, Polish, Portuguese, Romanian, Slovak, Slovene, Spanish, and Swedish.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Important documents, such as legislation, are translated into every official language and the European Parliament provides translation for documents and plenary sessions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Even though language policy is the responsibility of member states, EU institutions promote multilingualism among its citizens.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The most widely spoken language in the EU is English; the language is spoken by 50 per cent of the population and studied by 95 per cent of school students, although following the withdrawal of the United Kingdom only 2% of the population speak it natively.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] German and French are spoken by 29 per cent and 25 per cent of the population.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] More than half (59 per cent) of EU citizens are able to engage in a conversation in a language other than their mother tongue, and more than a tenth (11%) are quadrilingual.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Luxembourgish (in Luxembourg) and Turkish (in Cyprus) are the only two national languages that are not official languages of the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Catalan, Galician and Basque are not recognised official languages of the EU but have official status in Spain.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Therefore, official translations of the treaties are made into them and citizens have the right to correspond with the institutions in these languages.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] There are about 150 regional and minority languages in the EU, spoken by up to 50 million people.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages ratified by most EU states provides general guidelines that states can follow to protect their linguistic heritage.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Day of Languages is held annually on 26 September and is aimed at encouraging language learning across Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU has no formal connection to any religion.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Article 17 of the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union recognises the "status under national law of churches and religious associations" as well as that of "philosophical and non-confessional organisations".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The preamble to the Treaty on European Union mentions the "cultural, religious and humanist inheritance of Europe".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Discussion over the draft texts of the European Constitution and later the Treaty of Lisbon included proposals to mention Christianity or a god, or both, in the preamble of the text, but the idea faced opposition and was dropped.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Christians in the EU include Catholics of both Latin and Eastern Rite, numerous Protestant denominations with Lutherans, Anglicans, and Reformed forming the majority of Protestant affiliations, and the Eastern Orthodox Church.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 2009, the EU had an estimated Muslim population of 13 million, and an estimated Jewish population of over a million.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The other world religions of Buddhism, Hinduism, and Sikhism are also represented in the EU population.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Eurostat's Eurobarometer opinion polls showed in 2005 that 52 per cent of EU citizens believed in a god, 27 per cent in "some sort of spirit or life force", and 18 per cent had no form of belief.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Into the 21st century, many countries have experienced falling church attendance and membership.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The countries where the fewest people reported a religious belief were Estonia (16 per cent) and the Czech Republic (19 per cent).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The most religious countries were Malta (95 per cent, predominantly Catholic) as well as Cyprus and Romania (both predominantly Orthodox) each with about 90 per cent of citizens professing a belief in God.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Across the EU, belief was higher among women, older people, those with religious upbringing, those who left school at 15 or 16, and those "positioning themselves on the right of the political scale".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Basic education is an area where the EU's role is limited to supporting national governments.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In higher education, the policy was developed in the 1980s in programmes supporting exchanges and mobility.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The most visible of these has been the Erasmus Programme, a university exchange programme which began in 1987.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In its first 20 years, it supported international exchange opportunities for well over 1.5 million university and college students and became a symbol of European student life.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] There are similar programmes for school pupils and teachers, for trainees in vocational education and training, and for adult learners in the Lifelong Learning Programme 2007–2013.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] These programmes are designed to encourage a wider knowledge of other countries and to spread good practices in the education and training fields across the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Through its support of the Bologna Process, the EU is supporting comparable standards and compatible degrees across Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Scientific development is facilitated through the EU's Framework Programmes, the first of which started in 1984.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The aims of EU policy in this area are to co-ordinate and stimulate research.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The independent European Research Council allocates EU funds to European or national research projects.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] EU research and technological framework programmes deal in a number of areas, for example energy where the aim is to develop a diverse mix of renewable energy to help the environment and to reduce dependence on imported fuels.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Article 35 of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union affirms that "A high level of human health protection shall be ensured in the definition and implementation of all Union policies and activities".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Commission's Directorate-General for Health and Consumers seeks to align national laws on the protection of people's health, on the consumers' rights, on the safety of food and other products.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] All EU and many other European countries offer their citizens a free European Health Insurance Card which, on a reciprocal basis, provides insurance for emergency medical treatment insurance when visiting other participating European countries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] A directive on cross-border healthcare aims at promoting co-operation on health care between member states and facilitating access to safe and high-quality cross-border healthcare for European patients.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The life expectancy in the EU was 80.1 year at birth in 2021, among the highest in the world and around nine years higher than the world average.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In general, life expectancy is lower in Eastern Europe than in Western Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 2018, the EU region with the highest life expectancy was Madrid, Spain at 85.2 years, followed by the Spanish regions of La Rioja and Castilla y León both at 84.3 years, Trentino in Italy at 84.3 years and Île-de-France in France at 84.2 years.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU has also sought to coordinate the social security and health systems of member states to facilitate individuals exercising free movement rights and to ensure they maintain their ability to access social security and health services in other member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Since 2019 there has been a European commissioner for equality and the European Institute for Gender Equality has existed since 2007.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] A Directive on countering gender-based violence has been proposed.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In September 2022, a European Care strategy was approved in order to provide "quality, affordable and accessible care services".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Social Charter is the main body that recognises the social rights of European citizens.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 2020, the first ever European Union Strategy on LGBTIQ equality was approved under Helena Dalli mandate.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In December 2021, the commission announced the intention of codifying a union-wide law against LGBT hate crimes.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Since the creation of the European Union in 1993, it has developed its competencies in the area of justice and home affairs; initially at an intergovernmental level and later by supranationalism.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Accordingly, the union has legislated in areas such as extradition, family law, asylum law, and criminal justice.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU has also established agencies to co-ordinate police, prosecution and civil litigations across the member states: Europol for police co-operation, CEPOL for training of police forces and the Eurojust for co-operation between prosecutors and courts.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It also operates the EUCARIS database of vehicles and drivers, the Eurodac, the European Criminal Records Information System, the European Cybercrime Centre, FADO, PRADO and others.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Prohibitions against discrimination have a long standing in the treaties.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In more recent years, these have been supplemented by powers to legislate against discrimination based on race, religion, disability, age, and sexual orientation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] In 2009, the Lisbon Treaty gave legal effect to the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The charter is a codified catalogue of fundamental rights against which the EU's legal acts can be judged.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It consolidates many rights which were previously recognised by the Court of Justice and derived from the "constitutional traditions common to the member states".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Court of Justice has long recognised fundamental rights and has, on occasion, invalidated EU legislation based on its failure to adhere to those fundamental rights.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Signing the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR) is a condition for EU membership.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Previously, the EU itself could not accede to the convention as it is neither a state nor had the competence to accede.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Lisbon Treaty and Protocol 14 to the ECHR have changed this: the former binds the EU to accede to the convention while the latter formally permits it.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU is independent from the Council of Europe, although they share purpose and ideas, especially on the rule of law, human rights and democracy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Furthermore, the European Convention on Human Rights and European Social Charter, as well as the source of law for the Charter of Fundamental Rights are created by the Council of Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU has also promoted human rights issues in the wider world.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU opposes the death penalty and has proposed its worldwide abolition.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Abolition of the death penalty is a condition for EU membership.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] On 19 October 2020, the European Union revealed new plans to create a legal structure to act against human rights violations worldwide.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The new plan was expected to provide the European Union with greater flexibility to target and sanction those responsible for serious human rights violations and abuses around the world.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Cultural co-operation between member states has been an interest of the European Union since its inclusion as a community competency in the Maastricht Treaty.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Actions taken in the cultural area by the EU include the Culture 2000 seven-year programme, the European Cultural Month event, and orchestras such as the European Union Youth Orchestra.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Capital of Culture programme selects one or more cities in every year to assist the cultural development of that city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Sport is mainly the responsibility of the member states or other international organisations, rather than of the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] There are some EU policies that have affected sport, such as the free movement of workers, which was at the core of the Bosman ruling that prohibited national football leagues from imposing quotas on foreign players with EU member state citizenship.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Treaty of Lisbon requires any application of economic rules to take into account the specific nature of sport and its structures based on voluntary activity.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] This followed lobbying by governing organisations such as the International Olympic Committee and FIFA, due to objections over the application of free market principles to sport, which led to an increasing gap between rich and poor clubs.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The EU does fund a programme for Israeli, Jordanian, Irish, and British football coaches, as part of the Football 4 Peace project.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The flag of Europe consists of a circle of 12 golden stars on a blue background.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Originally designed in 1955 for the Council of Europe, the flag was adopted by the European Communities, the predecessors of the present European Union, in 1986.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The Council of Europe gave the flag a symbolic description in the following terms, although the official symbolic description adopted by the EU omits the reference to the "Western world".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Charles the Great, also known as Charlemagne (Latin: *Carolus Magnus*) and later recognised as *Pater Europae* ("Father of Europe"), has a symbolic relevance to Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The commission has named one of its central buildings in Brussels after Charlemagne and the city of Aachen has since 1949 awarded the Charlemagne Prize to champions of European unification.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Since 2008, the organisers of this prize, in conjunction with the European Parliament, have awarded the Charlemagne Youth Prize in recognition of similar efforts led by young people.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Media freedom is a fundamental right that applies to all member states of the European Union and its citizens, as defined in the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights as well as the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Within the EU enlargement process, guaranteeing media freedom is named a "key indicator of a country's readiness to become part of the EU".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The majority of media in the European Union are national-orientated, although some EU-wide media focusing on European affairs have emerged since the early 1990s, such as Euronews, Eurosport, EUobserver, EURACTIV or Politico Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Arte is a public Franco-German TV network that promotes programming in the areas of culture and the arts.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] 80 per cent of its programming are provided in equal proportion by the two member companies, while the remainder is being provided by the European Economic Interest Grouping *ARTE GEIE* and the channel's European partners.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The MEDIA Programme of the European Union has supported the European popular film and audiovisual industries since 1991.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] It provides support for the development, promotion and distribution of European works within Europe and beyond.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Union has had a significant positive economic effect on most member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] According to a 2019 study of the member states who joined from 1973 to 2004, "without European integration, per capita incomes would have been, on average, approximately 10% lower in the first ten years after joining the EU".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Greece was the exception reported by the study, which analysed up to 2008, "to avoid confounding effects from the global financial crisis".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] A 2021 study in the *Journal of Political Economy* found that the 2004 enlargement had aggregate beneficial economic effects on all groups in both the old and new member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The largest winners were the new member states, in particular unskilled labour in the new member states.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] The European Union is frequently cited as having made a major contribution to peace in Europe, in particular by pacifying border disputes, and to the spread of democracy, especially by encouraging democratic reforms in aspiring Eastern European member states after the collapse of the USSR.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] Scholar Thomas Risse wrote in 2009, "there is a consensus in the literature on Eastern Europe that the EU membership perspective had a huge anchoring effects for the new democracies." However, R.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/european-union-p03] At the same time, the union might provide through Article 7 of the Treaty on European Union an external constraint that prevents electoral autocracies, currently Hungary, from progressing into closed autocracies.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg is located at the southwestern foothills of the Black Forest, on the Dreisam River, a tributary of the Elz.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It is Germany's southwestern- and southernmost city with a population exceeding 100,000.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It lies in the Breisgau, one of Germany's warmest regions, in the south of the Upper Rhine Plain.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Its city limits reach from the Schauinsland summit (1,284 metres (4,213 ft)) in the Black Forest to 3 kilometres (1.9 mi) east of the French border, while Switzerland is 42 kilometres (26 mi) to the south.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city is situated in the major wine-growing region of Baden and, together with Offenburg, serves as a tourist entry-point to the scenic Black Forest.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] According to meteorological statistics, Freiburg held the all-time German temperature record of 40.2 °C (104.4 °F) from 2003 to 2015.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] An old university town and archiepiscopal seat, it was incorporated in the early 12th century and soon became a commercial, intellectual and ecclesiastical center for the Upper Rhine region.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The University of Freiburg (*Albert-Ludwigs-Universität Freiburg*), founded in 1457, is one of Germany's oldest universities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg's main landmark is the Freiburg Minster (*Freiburger Münster*), which was built between c.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] 1200 and 1513 and has been described as "Gothic architectural masterpiece".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The old town is traversed by an extensive system of runnels called Bächle (lit.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] *small streams*), that are fed with water from the Dreisam and run on the side of almost all streets and alleys, giving the city a unique touch.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg has a high standard of living, and is known for its advanced environmental practices, which is embodied by local housing projects such as the creation of the sustainable district of Vauban.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The dialect spoken in Freiburg is classified as (Upper Rhenish) Low Alemannic, and therefore most closely related to the other dialects of Baden north of Markgräflerland and south of Karlsruhe, to most dialects historically spoken in Alsace (Alsatian), and to Basel German.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg was founded by Konrad and Duke Berthold III of the House of Zähringen in 1120 as a free market town; hence its name, which translates to "free (or independent) town".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] *Frei* means "free", and *Burg*, like the modern English word "borough", was used in those days for an incorporated city or town, usually one with some degree of autonomy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The German word *Burg* also means "a fortified town", as in Hamburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Thus, it is likely that the name of this place means a "fortified town of free citizens".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] This town was strategically located at a junction of trade routes between the Mediterranean Sea and the North Sea regions, and the Rhine and Danube rivers.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1200, Freiburg's population numbered approximately 6,000 people.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] At about that time, under the rule of Bertold V, the last duke of Zähringen, the town began construction of its Freiburg Minster on the site of an older parish church.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Begun in the Romanesque style, it was continued and completed 1513 for the most part as a Gothic edifice.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1218, when Bertold V died, then Egino V von Urach, the count of Urach assumed the title of Freiburg's count as Egino I von Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The town council did not trust the new nobles and wrote down its established rights in a document.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] At the end of the thirteenth century there was a feud between the town of Freiburg and their lord, Count Egino II of Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Egino II raised taxes and sought to limit the citizens' freedom, after which the Freiburgers used catapults to destroy the count's castle atop the Schloßberg, a hill that overlooks the town.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The furious count called on his brother-in-law the Prince-Bishop of Strasbourg, Conrad of Lichtenberg, for help.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The bishop responded by marching with his army to Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] According to an old Freiburg legend, a butcher named Hauri stabbed the Bishop of Strasbourg to death on 29 July 1299.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It was a Pyrrhic victory, since henceforth the citizens of Freiburg had to pay an annual expiation of 300 marks in silver to the count of Freiburg until 1368.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1366 the counts of Freiburg made another failed attempt to occupy the town during a night raid.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Eventually the inhabitants were fed up with their lords, and in 1368 Freiburg purchased its independence from them.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The town turned itself over to the protection of the Habsburgs, who allowed the town to retain a large measure of freedom.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Most of the nobles of the city died in the battle of Sempach (1386).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The patrician family Schnewlin took control of the city until the guildsmen revolted.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The guilds became more powerful than the patricians by 1389.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The silver mines in Mount Schauinsland provided an important source of capital for Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] This silver made Freiburg one of the richest cities in Europe, and in 1327 Freiburg minted its own coin, the *Rappenpfennig*.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1377 the cities of Freiburg, Basel, Colmar, and Breisach entered into a monetary alliance known as the *Genossenschaft des Rappenpfennigs* (Rappenpfennig Collective).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] This alliance facilitated commerce among the cities and lasted until the end of the sixteenth century.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] There were 8,000–9,000 people living in Freiburg between the thirteenth and fourteenth centuries, and 30 churches and monasteries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] At the end of the fourteenth century the veins of silver were dwindling, and by 1460 only approximately 6,000 people still lived within Freiburg's city walls.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] A university town, Freiburg evolved from its focus on mining to become a cultural centre for the arts and sciences.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The end of the Middle Ages and the dawn of the Renaissance was a time of both advances and tragedy for Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1457, Albrecht VI, Regent of Further Austria, established Albert-Ludwigs-Universität, one of Germany's oldest universities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1498, Emperor Maximilian I held a Reichstag in Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1520, the town ratified a set of legal reforms, widely considered the most progressive of the time.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The aim was to find a balance between traditions and old Roman Law.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The reforms were well received, especially the sections dealing with civil process law, punishment, and the town's constitution.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1520, Freiburg decided not to take part in the Reformation and became an important centre for Catholicism on the Upper Rhine.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Erasmus moved here after Basel accepted the Reformation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1536, a strong and persistent belief in witchcraft led to the town's first witch-hunt.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The need to find a scapegoat for calamities such as the Black Plague, which claimed 2,000 area residents (25% of the town's population) in 1564, led to an escalation in witch-hunting that peaked in 1599.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] A plaque on the old town wall marks the spot where burnings were carried out.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The seventeenth, eighteenth, and nineteenth centuries were turbulent times for Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] At the beginning of the Thirty Years' War in 1618, its population numbered between 10,000 to 14,000; when it ended in 1648, only 2,000 remained.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In August 1644, it was the site of the Battle of Freiburg, said to be the bloodiest battle of the war in terms of percentage of casualties.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Between 1648 and 1805, when the town was not under French occupation, it was the administrative headquarters of Further Austria, the Habsburg territories in southwest Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1805 the town, together with the Breisgau and Ortenau areas, became part of Baden.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1828, after the Archdiocese of Freiburg was founded, Freiburg became seat of a Catholic archbishop.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg was heavily bombed during World War II.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In May 1940, aircraft of the Luftwaffe mistakenly dropped approximately 60 bombs on Freiburg near the railway station, killing 57 people, most of them civilians and including 22 children.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] This was reported by the official German news agency as an attack by the Western Allies, and retaliation against them was threatened.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Freiburg police commander subsequently established that the bombs were German, but the full story was not published until many years later.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] On 27 November 1944, a raid by more than 300 bombers of RAF Bomber Command (Operation Tigerfish) destroyed a large portion of the city centre, with the notable exception of the *Münster*—which was only lightly damaged—and houses southeast of it.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] After the war, the city was rebuilt on its medieval plan.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] On 22 October 1940, the Nazi Gauleiter of Baden, Robert Heinrich Wagner, ordered the deportation of all of Baden's and 350 of Freiburg's Jewish population.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] They were deported to Camp Gurs in the south of France, where many died.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] On 18 July 1942, the remaining Baden and Freiburg Jews were transferred to Auschwitz in German-occupied Poland, where almost all were murdered.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] A memorial has been created in the form of the 'footprint' in marble on the site of the city's original synagogue, which was burned down on 9 November 1938, during the pogrom known as *Kristallnacht*.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The memorial is a fountain and contains a bronze plaque commemorating the original building and the Jewish community which perished.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The pavements of Freiburg carry memorials to individual victims, in the form of brass plates outside their former residences.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] There was a camp for Sinti and Romani people (see *Romani Holocaust*) in the city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It was occupied by the French Army on 21 April 1945, and Freiburg was soon allotted to the French Zone of Occupation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In December 1945 Freiburg became the seat of government for the German state of Baden, which was merged into Baden-Württemberg in 1952.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The French Army maintained a presence in Freiburg until 1991, when the last French Army division left the city, and left Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Union for Aromanian Language and Culture, an Aromanian cultural organization, was founded in 1985 in Freiburg by the Aromanian professor Vasile Barba.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] On the site of the former French Army base, a new neighborhood for 5,000 people, Vauban, began in the late 1990s as a "sustainable model district".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Solar power provides electricity to many of the households in this small community.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Because of its scenery, relatively warm and sunny climate, and easy access to the Black Forest, Freiburg is a hub for regional tourism.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 2010, Freiburg was voted as the Academy of Urbanism's European City of the Year in recognition of the exemplary sustainable urbanism it had implemented over the preceding decades.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The longest cable car run in Germany, which is 3.6 kilometres (2.2 mi) long, runs from Günterstal up to a nearby mountain called *Schauinsland*.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city has an unusual system of gutters (called *Freiburg Bächle*) that run throughout its centre.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] These *Bächle*, once used to provide water to fight fires and feed livestock, are constantly flowing with water diverted from the Dreisam.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] They were never intended to be used for sewage, and even in the Middle Ages such use could lead to harsh penalties.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] During the summer, the running water provides natural cooling of the air, and offers a pleasant gurgling sound.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It is said that if one accidentally falls or steps into a *Bächle*, they will marry a Freiburger, or 'Bobbele'.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The *Augustinerplatz* is one of the central squares in the old city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Formerly the location of an Augustinian monastery that became the Augustiner Museum in 1921, it is now a popular social space for Freiburg's younger residents.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It has a number of restaurants and bars, including the local brewery 'Feierling', which has a Biergarten.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] On warm summer nights, hundreds of students gather here.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] At the centre of the old city is the Münsterplatz or Cathedral Square, Freiburg's largest square.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] A farmers' market is held here every day except Sundays.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] This is the site of Freiburg's Münster, a gothic minster cathedral constructed of red sandstone, built between 1200 and 1530 and noted for its towering spire.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Historical Merchants' Hall (*Historisches Kaufhaus*), is a Late Gothic building on the south side of Freiburg's *Münsterplatz*.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Built between 1520 and 1530, it was once the center of the financial life of the region.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Its façade is decorated with statues and the coat of arms of four Habsburg emperors.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The *Altes Rathaus*, or old city hall, was completed in 1559 and has a painted façade.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The *Platz der alten Synagoge* "Old Synagogue Square" is one of the more important squares on the outskirts of the historic old city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The square was the location of a synagogue until it was destroyed on *Kristallnacht* in 1938.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Zum Roten Bären, the oldest hotel in Germany, is located along *Oberlinden* near the Swabian Gate.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The *Siegesdenkmal*, or victory monument, is a monument to the German victory in the Franco-Prussian War in 1871.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It is situated at the northern edge of the historic city center of Freiburg and was built by Karl Friedrich Moest.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In everyday language of people living in Freiburg, it serves as an orientation marker or as a meeting place.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] To the east of the city centre, the Schlossberg hill provides extensive views over the city and surrounding region.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The castle (Schloss) from which the hill takes its name was demolished in the 1740s, and only ruins remain.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Schlossberg retained its importance to the city, however, and 150 years ago the city leaders opened up walks and views to make the mountain available to the public.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Today, the Schlossbergbahn funicular railway connects the city centre to the hill.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Other museums in the city include the Archaeology Colombischlössle Museum.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Panoramic view of Freiburg, seen from Schlossberg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg is bordered by the Black Forest mountains Rosskopf and Bromberg to the east, Schönberg and Tuniberg to the south, with the Kaiserstuhl hill region to the west.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Köppen climate classification classifies Freiburg's climate as temperate oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*; Trewartha: *Dobk*).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Thus, July and August are, along with Karlsruhe, the warmest within Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Winters are moderate but usually with some frosts at night.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] More year-round rain occurs here than in the Rhine plateau.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city is close to the Kaiserstuhl, a range of hills of volcanic origin located a few kilometers away, which is one of the warmest places in Germany and therefore considered as a viticultural area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In June 1995, the Freiburg city council adopted a resolution that it would permit construction only of "low-energy buildings" on municipal land, and all new buildings must comply with certain low energy specifications.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The neighbourhoods of Vauban and Rieselfeld were developed and built in the late 1990s in accordance with the principles of sustainability.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city is also home to a branch of the Federal Office for Radiation Protection, as well as solar industry and research.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The citizens of Freiburg are known in Germany for their love of cycling and recycling.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg is host to a number of international organisations, in particular, ICLEI – Local Governments for Sustainability, International Solar Energy Society, and the City Mayors Foundation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Politically, it is a longtime stronghold of the Alliance 90/The Greens, who have seen consistent success since the 1990s and have been the largest party on the city council since 2004.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] For many years, they performed more strongly in Freiburg than any other major city: former mayor Dieter Salomon, who served from 2002 to 2018, was the first member of the Greens to hold such an office in a city of over 100,000 people.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The current mayor of Freiburg is Martin Horn since 2018.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] He was previously a member of the Social Democratic Party (SPD) but left before running for mayor.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In the election, he was supported by the SPD and the Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Freiburg city council governs the city alongside the Mayor.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg belonged to Austria until 1805 and remained Catholic, although surrounding villages like Haslach, Opfingen, Tiengen, and the surrounding land ruled by the Margrave of Baden became Protestant as a result of the Reformation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city was part of the Diocese of Konstanz until 1821.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] That same year, Freiburg became an episcopal see of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Due to a dispute between the government of Baden and the Holy See, the archbishop officially took office in 1827.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The borders of the archdiocese correspond with the borders of the former province of Baden and the former Margraviate of Hohenzollern.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The cathedral, in which the bishop resides, is Freiburg Minster.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Also, part of the ecclesiastical province of Freiburg are the suffragan dioceses of Mainz and Rottenburg-Stuttgart.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Until 1929, the dioceses of Limburg and Fulda also belonged to this ecclesiastical province.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Archbishop of Freiburg holds the title of metropolitan and the German headquarters of the link to Caritas Germany is in Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Saint George (the flag of Freiburg has the cross of George), Lambert of Maastricht and the catacomb saint, Alexander, are the patron saints of Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Many works of art depicting these saints are in the Freiburg Minster, on the Minster square, just as in the museums and archives of the city, including some by Hans Baldung Grien, Hans Holbein the Younger and Gregorius Sickinger.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1805, with the attack of Breisgau on the Grand Duchy of Baden by a Catholic ruler, many Protestants moved into the city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Since 2007, any Protestants who are not part of a 'free church' belong to the newly founded deanery of Freiburg as part of the parish of Südbaden which in itself is a part of the Landeskirche Baden.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The seat of the Evangelical Lutheran Church in Baden, a free Lutheran church, is situated in Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] There are multiple other free Protestant churches: e.g., the Calvary Chapel or Chrischona International.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] An old congregation has existed in Freiburg since the late 1900s, which utilises the old monastery church of the Ursulines in the black monastery at the border of the old city center.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Maria Schutz has been made available for Masses by Greek, Serbian, Russian and Rumanian Orthodox congregations.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Jews are said to have lived in the city before 1230, but it was only after 1230 that they supposedly founded an official community in the Webergasse (a small street within the town center).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The counts of Freiburg bought the lucrative Schutzjude, which means that all personal information on Jews living in Freiburg was directly sent to Konrad II and his co-reigning son Friedrich.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The two issued a comprising letter promising safety and liberty to all local Jews on 12 October 1338.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It lost all value shortly after, however, on 1 January 1349.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Although the plague had not yet broken out in the city, Jews were accused of having spread it and taken into custody.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] All Jews except pregnant women were burned alive on 31 January 1349.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The remaining children were forced to be baptised.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] This pogrom left Jews very hesitant to resettle in the city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 1401, the city council decreed a regulation banning all Jews from Freiburg (orig.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Middle High German dialect: "daz dekein Jude ze Friburg niemmerme sin sol".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] This was officially reaffirmed by King Sigismund with a ban for life (orig.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Not until 1809 were Jews again allowed permanent residence within the city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] They subsequently founded a Jewish community in 1836.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] At the Kristallnacht in 1938, the synagogue, built in 1870, was set afire.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Numerous shops and apartments of Jewish citizens of Freiburg were devastated and plundered by National Socialists without the intervention of police or fire department.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Male, wealthy, Jewish citizens were kidnapped and taken to concentration camps (in Buchenwald and Dachau) where they were subjected to forced labor or executed and their money and property stolen.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] On 22 October 1940, the remaining Jews of Baden and Pfalz were deported to Camp de Gurs in southern France.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] One among many collecting points was Annaplatz.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] So-called 'Stolpersteine', tiles with names and dates on them, commemorate the victims of the prosecution of Jews during the Nazi-Era in the city's cobble.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Journalist Käthe Vordtriede of the Volkswacht even received two Stolpersteine to commemorate her life.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The first one was inserted into the ground in front of the Vordtriede-Haus Freiburg in 2006 and the second one in front of the Basler Hof, the regional authorities, in spring 2013.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] This was also the seat of the Gestapo until 1941, where unrelenting people were cruelly interrogated, held prisoner or deported.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The only solutions were flight or emigration.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Vordtriede family managed to escape in time.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg is a center of academia and research, in which numerous intellectual figures and Nobel Laureates have lived, worked, and taught.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city houses one of the oldest and most renowned of German universities, the Albert Ludwig University of Freiburg, as well as its medical center.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Home to some of the greatest minds of the West, including such eminent figures as Johann Eck, Max Weber, Edmund Husserl, Martin Heidegger, and Friedrich Hayek, it is one of Europe's top research and teaching institutions.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city is home to the IES Abroad European Union program, which allows students to study the development and activities of the EU.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] This is in addition to an Environmental Science and Sustainability program focused on Freiburg's famed green lifestyle and infrastructure.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] IES Abroad also offers a German Language and Area Studies program where visiting students get to take classes at the University of Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The DFG / LFA Freiburg, a French-German high school established by the 1963 Élysée Treaty, is in the city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] UWC Robert Bosch College is among the newest members of the United World Colleges (UWC) movement, one of its eighteen colleges around the world, having started accepting students in September 2014.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg has a large pedestrian zone in the city centre where no motor cars are allowed.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg also has an extensive public transport system, operated by the city-owned VAG Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The backbone of the system is the Freiburg tramway network, supplemented by feeder buses.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The tram network is very popular as the low fares allow for unlimited transport in the city and surrounding area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Furthermore, any ticket for a concert, sports or other event is also valid for use on public transport.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The tram network is so vast that 70% of the population live within 500m of a tram stop with a tram every 7–8 mins.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg is on the main Frankfurt am Main – Basel railway line, with frequent and fast long-distance passenger services from the Freiburg Hauptbahnhof to major German and other European cities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Other railway lines run east into the Black Forest and west to Breisach and are served by the Breisgau S-Bahn.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The line to Breisach is the remaining stub of the Freiburg–Colmar international railway, severed in 1945 when the railway bridge over the Rhine at Breisach was destroyed, and was never replaced.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city also is served by the A5 Frankfurt am Main – Basel motorway.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg is served by EuroAirport Basel-Mulhouse-Freiburg in France, close to the borders of both Germany and Switzerland, 70 km (43 mi) south of Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Karlsruhe/Baden-Baden Airport is approximately 100 km (62 mi) north of Freiburg and is also served by several airlines.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The nearest larger international airports include Zurich (130 km (81 mi)), Stuttgart (200 km (120 mi)), and Frankfurt/Main (260 km (160 mi)).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The nearby Flugplatz Freiburg (IATA: **QFB**, ICAO: **EDTF**), a small airfield in the Messe, Freiburg district, lacks commercial service but is used for private aviation.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Car share websites such as BlaBlaCar are commonly used among Freiburg residents, since they are considered relatively safe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The investment in transport has resulted in a large increase in both cycle, pedestrian and public transport usage with projections of car journeys accounting for 29% of journey times.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Freiburger FC won the 1907 German football championship.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Afterwards, the city experienced a 115-year drought where no sports team won a national championship again.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 2022, the drought was finally ended by the Eisvögel USC Freiburg who won the 1.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg is home to football teams SC Freiburg, which plays at the Europa-Park Stadion and is represented in the 1. or 2.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Bundesliga since 1978, and Freiburger FC.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 2016, SC Freiburg got promoted to the highest league for the fifth time in its club history.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The club became generally known in Germany for its steady staffing policy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Achim Stocker was president of the club from 1972 until his death in 2009.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Longtime coach was Volker Finke (1991–2007), to whose initiative the football school of the club goes back.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In 2004, SC Freiburg celebrated its 100th anniversary.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Since December 2011, the coach is Christian Streich.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The women's team of SC Freiburg plays in the first Women's Bundesliga.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg is represented in the first women's basketball league by the Eisvögel (Kingfisher) USC Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In the season 2005/2006, the Kingfishers took second place after the end of the second round, in the season 2006/2007 it was the fourth place.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The men's team of the USC played in the 2009/10 season in the ProA (2nd Bundesliga).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Freiburg men's team played their last first-division season in 1998/1999.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Currently, season 2018/19, the men's team plays in the Oberliga and the women's team in the regional league.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Freiburg also has the EHC Freiburg ice hockey team, which plays at the Franz-Siegel Halle.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In the season 2003/2004 the EHC Freiburg (the wolves) played in the DEL, the highest German ice hockey league.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Currently, season 2018/19, they play in the second league (DEL2).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Additionally, there is the RC Freiburg Rugby union team, which competes in the second Bundesliga South (Baden Württemberg).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The home ground of the club, the only rugby sports field in the wider area, is located in March-Hugstetten.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Then, there is the volleyball men's team of the FT 1844 Freiburg, which plays in the second Bundesliga since 2001 and the handball women's team of the HSG Freiburg, which plays in the 3rd Women's Handball League.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] From 1925 to 1984, the Schauinsland Races took place on an old logging track.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The course is still used periodically for European Hill Climb Championships.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The association Kunst in Freiburg is an association of galleries and exhibition spaces in Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] They organize joint exhibition projects such as the annual art night *nocturne*.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Biennial for Freiburg, which is organized by the association Perspektiven für Kunst in Freiburg e.V., has been taking place since 2021.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Founded in 1827, the Kunstverein Freiburg is one of the oldest in Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] In the building of the former Marienbad, the Kunstverein presents current trends and, above all, young positions in contemporary art at an international level.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Augustiner Museum presents its renowned collection of art from the Middle Ages to the Baroque as well as 19th century paintings.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The former monastery church has been transformed into an impressive, modern museum building that makes a visit to the museum a real experience.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Museum of Contemporary Art is a forum for important social debates, equally committed to art and the public.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Changing exhibitions reflect elementary themes of our time.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] From the rich collection of 20th and 21st century works, a selection of classical modernism is always on display.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Colombischlössle Archaeological Museum: The neo-Gothic palace houses precious finds from the Stone Age to the early Middle Ages.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The Alamanni treasure chamber displays jewelry and magnificent weapons from Alamanni graves.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Museum of Nature and Man: With its collections on natural history and ethnology, the museum is dedicated to the diversity and uniqueness of natural and cultural environments.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It is an entertaining and educational place for the whole family.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Museum of City History: Treasures from 900 years of the city's history can be seen in the late baroque house of the artist Johann Christian Wentzinger.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Documentation Center for National Socialism Freiburg: Built in 1936, the former public transport office on Rotteckring will be home to the National Socialist Documentation Center by 2025, providing information about the National Socialist era in Freiburg.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Iranian president Mahmoud Ahmadinejad's controversial comments, which included questioning the dimension of the Holocaust, have sparked discussions concerning Freiburg's relationship with Isfahan.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Immediately following the comments, Freiburg mayor Salomon postponed a trip to Isfahan, but most people involved, especially those in the Alliance '90/The Greens party, were opposed to cancelling the relationship.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city's coat of arms is Argent a cross Gules, the St George's Cross.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Saint George is the city's patron saint.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The cross also appears on the city's flag, which dates from about 1368, and is identical to that of England, which has the same patron.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The city also has a seal that can be seen in a few places in the inner city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] It is a stylised depiction of the façade of the *Wasserschlössle*, a castle-like waterworks facility built into a hill that overlooks the residential district of Wiehre.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] The seal depicts a three-towered red castle on a white background, with green-clad trumpeters atop the two outer towers.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/freiburg-im-breisgau] Beneath the castle is a gold fleur-de-lis.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] The daughter of a streetcar driver and a ticket collector, Kraft graduated in 1980, and first trained as a bank clerk with Dresdner Bank.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] She commenced her studies in economics at Comprehensive University of Duisburg in 1982, and studied at King's College London in 1986 and 1987.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] She completed her studies in Duisburg in 1989.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] From 1989 until 2001, Kraft was a consultant and project manager at ZENIT GmbH ('Centre for Innovation and Technology') in Mülheim an der Ruhr, and was head of the local European Info Centre.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] She was drawn to politics after becoming head of a works council and struggling to find a place for her son in a nursery.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] At the 2000 North Rhine-Westphalia state election, she was elected to the Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Initially representing electoral district 74 (Mülheim II-Essen VII), she switched to electoral district 64 (Mülheim I) for the election in 2005.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] On 24 April 2001, she replaced Detlev Samland as Minister for Federal and European Affairs, and then under Minister-President Peer Steinbrück, served from 12 November 2002 until 31 May 2005 as Minister for Science and Research.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Kraft was a SPD delegate to the Federal Convention for the purpose of electing the President of Germany in 2004, 2009, 2010 and 2012.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] After the SPD lost the 2005 state election in North Rhine-Westphalia, Kraft was elected leader of the SPD's parliamentary group with 95.7% of the votes, hence becoming the Opposition Leader in the state.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2007, she was elected chairperson of the SPD in North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] On 13 November 2009, Kraft was elected as one of the four vice chairs of the federal SPD under chairman Sigmar Gabriel, receiving the highest overall vote.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] A party congress in February 2010 affirmed that she was the SPD's candidate for Minister-President at the May 2010 state election.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] After many parallel negotiations and various coalitions, Kraft was elected Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia on 14 July 2010 on the second ballot with a sufficient majority of votes, coming from the SPD and Alliance 90/The Greens, while the Left Party abstained.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Kraft formed a minority government with ministers of Social Democrats and Greens.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] It was the first time in Germany that a coalition has attempted to rule one of the 16 federal states without a proper majority, with the only exception being a red–green alliance governing Berlin for some months in 2001–2002 without a majority.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] For nearly two years, Kraft ruled the state without a regular majority, pulling votes for each initiative from opposition parties on the right or the left.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Together with the deputy governor, Sylvia Löhrmann from the Green Party, Kraft dubbed her government the "invitation coalition".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] After decades of ideological rivalry in the state over the structure of secondary schools, both Kraft and Löhrmann later succeeded in negotiating a cross-party agreement with the centre-right Christian Democratic Union that is to ensure peace until 2023.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Kraft got attention for a eulogy she gave after a stampede killed 21 people at the Love Parade music festival in July 2010, less than two weeks after she became state premier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] When she gave her speech at a memorial ceremony, she spoke of the hours she spent waiting to hear from her son, who was at the event, unsure if he was injured or unharmed, alive or dead.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In October 2010, Kraft was elected President of the Bundesrat, according to the customary rotation of the presidency between the Bundesländer.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] She assumed office on 1 November 2010, becoming the first female office holder, remaining in office until 31 October 2011.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] At an SPD convention in Berlin in December 2011, Kraft was confirmed in her vice-chairmanship by 97 percent of party members, the best result for a board member.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Krafts failure to get her 2012 budget plans passed after a court ruled a supplementary budget for 2010 unconstitutional forced her to call an early election and left her exposed to charges of fiscal incompetence.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Kraft had hoped to win backing from the opposition FDP for the budget but their long-standing objections were not overcome in time for the vote.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] The resulting election saw the SPD-Green coalition win a nine-seat majority and allowed Kraft to remain in office.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Cabinet Kraft II is quite similar to Cabinet Kraft I.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] This vaulted Kraft into the top rank of German politicians, prompting speculation that she might be the strongest contender to lead the party against Merkel and potentially succeed her as chancellor.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] However, she soon announced that she did not want to become the SPD's candidate for chancellor, preferring instead to stay in her home state for the five-year term she had just won.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2013, Kraft initially opposed national SPD leaders who opted to join Merkel as junior partner for the second time.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] However, she subsequently was part of the SPD team led by Sigmar Gabriel, which led the negotiations towards forming a new German government with Chancellor Angela Merkel's CDU/CSU bloc.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] She headed the SPD's delegation in the energy working group and vocally defended the coal industry, which has a sizeable presence in her state; her co-chair from the CDU/CSU was Peter Altmaier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2014, Kraft's government plans record spending of 62 billion euros ($85 billion) while trimming the deficit by a quarter to 2.4 billion euros.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] At the same time, she has repeatedly criticized Merkel's austerity policies during the debt crisis.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In March 2014, Kraft hosted Chinese President Xi Jinping in Duisburg as he visited the last stop on the Yuxinou Railway between Europe and Asia.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Following her party's loss in the 2017 state elections, Kraft remained a member of the State Parliament where she currently serves on the Committee on Sports.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] She also joined the supervisory board of RAG AG.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2019, her official portrait – a photograph made by Jim Rakete – was unveiled to the public.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2020, she announced her intention not to run again in the 2022 state elections.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2012, Kraft placed investment in renewable energy at the center of her second term's agenda, stating that more than 30 per cent of electricity in NRW should be coming from renewable sources by 2025.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2013, Kraft called on Angela Merkel to use tax revenue to cut electricity costs for consumers by 25 percent.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2013, Kraft led the Bundesrat opposition to a tax agreement with Switzerland, eventually blocking it as too easy on tax dodgers.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Under the proposed law, Germans with untaxed wealth in Switzerland would have been able to legitimize their holdings and retain their anonymity in exchange for paying a one-off penalty charge and submitting to a future withholding tax.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2013, the heir of a prominent Jewish art dealer Alfred Flechtheim, who fled Nazi Germany, urged the state of North Rhine-Westphalia to relinquish paintings by Paul Klee and Juan Gris that he says were lost due to Nazi persecution; Kraft declined to comment.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Alongside Senator Catherine Troendle, Kraft served as co-chairwoman of the German-French Friendship Group set up by the German Bundesrat and the French Senate.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] With 2014 marking the centenary of the start of World War I, Kraft inaugurated a memorial for the Armistice Day in Ablain-Saint-Nazaire alongside French President François Hollande and German Defense Minister Ursula von der Leyen, as well as British and Belgian officials.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] On 26 March 2015, Kraft joined Merkel, Hollande and Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy of Spain at the crash site of Germanwings Flight 9525 in the Massif des Trois-Évêchés for a memorial; North Rhine-Westphalia was the state where the plane was headed and many of the 144 passengers lived.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] One day later, she and Germany's President Joachim Gauck attended a memorial service in the western town of Haltern for 16 students and two teachers from the local high school who were killed in the crash.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Throughout her political career, Hannelore Kraft has received several distinctions in recognition of her public service and contributions to social welfare.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2007, she was awarded the Ehrenring des Rheinlandes (Rhineland Ring of Honor), followed in 2010 by the Order of Merit of North Rhine-Westphalia, the highest award granted by her home state.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Her commitment to social justice and the welfare state was further acknowledged in 2012 when she received the Marie-Juchacz-Plakette, the most prestigious honor bestowed by the Arbeiterwohlfahrt for social engagement.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] In 2018, following her tenure as Minister-President, Hannelore Kraft was decorated with the Great Cross with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany, marking a significant recognition of her service at the federal level.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] The couple celebrated their church wedding in Namibia in October 2012.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/hannelore-kraft] Kraft was formerly a Catholic but later converted to Protestantism, joining the Evangelical Church in the Rhineland, a member church of the Evangelical Church in Germany.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/metelen] The town history dates back to 889 AD, when it was first mentioned in an official document.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/metelen] Metelen is known for its aviary and, as the whole Münsterland region, as a great cycling area.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In the Middle Ages, Montpellier was an important city of the Crown of Aragon (and was the birthplace of James I), and then of Majorca, before its sale to France in 1349.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Established in 1220, the University of Montpellier is one of the oldest universities in the world and has the oldest medical school still in operation, with notable alumni such as Petrarch, Nostradamus and François Rabelais.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Above the medieval city, the ancient citadel of Montpellier is a stronghold built in the seventeenth century by Louis XIII.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Since the 1990s, Montpellier has experienced one of the strongest economic and demographic growths in the country.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Its urban area has experienced the highest population growth in France since the year 2000.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Numbering 70,000, students comprise nearly one-fourth of its population, one of the highest such proportions in Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Its living environment, with one of Europe's largest pedestrian areas, along with its rich cultural life and Mediterranean climate, explains the enthusiasm for the city, which is nicknamed the "Gifted".
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier was nominated for "Best Emerging Culture City of the Year 2017" by the think tank LCD.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] It is ranked as a Sufficiency city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In the Early Middle Ages, the nearby episcopal town of Maguelone was the major settlement in the area, but raids by pirates encouraged settlement a little farther inland.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In 737 Charles Martel destroyed Maguelone.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier, first mentioned in a document of 985, was founded under a local feudal dynasty, the Guilhem, who combined two hamlets and built a castle and walls around the united settlement.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The name is from medieval Latin *mons pisleri*, "Woad Mountain" referring to the woad (Latin *pastellus*, *pestellus*) used for dyeing locally.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] There is no real "mountain" in the area, with the *mons* referring to a pile of stones.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In 986 the Lords of Montpellier begin with William I of Montpellier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In the 10th century the town consisted of two portions, Montpellier and Montpelliéret.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The two surviving towers of the city walls, the *Tour des Pins* and the *Tour de la Babotte*, were built later, around the year 1200.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier came to prominence in the 12th century—as a trading centre, with trading links across the Mediterranean world, and a rich Jewish cultural life that flourished within traditions of tolerance of Muslims, Jews and Cathars—and later of its Protestants.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] William VIII of Montpellier gave freedom for all to teach medicine in Montpellier in 1180.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The city's faculties of law and medicine were established in 1220 by Cardinal Conrad of Urach, legate of Pope Honorius III; the medical faculty has, over the centuries, been one of the major centres for the teaching of medicine in Europe.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] This era marked the high point of Montpellier's prominence.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The city became a possession of the Kings of Aragon in 1204 by the marriage of Peter II of Aragon with Marie of Montpellier, who was given the city and its dependencies as part of her dowry.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier gained a charter in 1204 when Peter and Marie confirmed the city's traditional freedoms and granted the city the right to choose twelve governing consuls annually.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Under the Kings of Aragon, Montpellier became a very important city, a major economic centre and the primary centre for the spice trade in the Kingdom of France.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] It was the second or third most important city of France at that time, with some 40,000 inhabitants before the Black Death.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier remained a possession of the crown of Aragon until it passed to James III of Majorca, who sold the city to the French king Philip VI in 1349, to raise funds for his ongoing struggle with Peter IV of Aragon.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] From the middle of the 14th century until the French Revolution (1789), Montpellier was part of the province of Languedoc.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In the 14th century, Pope Urban VIII gave Montpellier a new monastery dedicated to Saint Peter, noteworthy for the very unusual porch of its chapel, supported by two high, somewhat rocket-like towers.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] With its importance steadily increasing, the city finally gained a bishop, who moved from Maguelone in 1536, and the huge monastery chapel became a cathedral.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In 1432, Jacques Cœur established himself in the city and it became an important economic centre, until 1481 when Marseilles overshadowed it in this role.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] At the time of the Reformation in the 16th century, many of the inhabitants of Montpellier became Protestants (or Huguenots as they were known in France) and the city became a stronghold of Protestant resistance to the Catholic French crown.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier was among the most important of the 66 *villes de sûreté* ('cities of protection' or 'protected cities') that the Edict of Nantes granted to the Huguenots.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The city's political institutions and the university were all handed over to the Huguenots.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Increasing tension with Paris led to King Louis XIII besieging the city in 1622.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] A truce ended 40 days of bombardment on 12 October 1622, with the Huguenots agreeing to the peace settlement on 18 October.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Peace terms called for the dismantling of the city's fortifications and the building of the royal Citadel of Montpellier to secure the city for the government.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The university and consulate were taken over by the Catholic party.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Even before the Edict of Alès in 1629, Protestant rule was dead and the *ville de sûreté* was no more.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Louis XIV made Montpellier capital of Bas Languedoc, and the town started to embellish itself, by building the Promenade du Peyrou, the Esplanade and a large number of houses in the historic centre.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] After the French Revolution, the city became the capital of the much smaller Department of Hérault.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] During the 19th century the city thrived on the wine culture that it was able to produce due to the abundance of sun throughout the year.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The wine consumption in France allowed Montpellier's citizens to become very wealthy until in the 1890s the phylloxera induced fungal disease had spread amongst the vineyards and the people were no longer able to grow the grapes needed for wine.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] During the repression of January and February 1894, the police conducted raids targeting the anarchists living there, without much success.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] After this the city grew because it welcomed French repatriates from Algeria and other parts of northern Africa after Algeria's independence from France.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In the 21st century Montpellier is between France's number seventh and eighth largest city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The city had another influx in population more recently, largely due to the student population, who make up about one-fourth of Montpellier's population.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The school of medicine kickstarted the city's thriving university culture, though many other universities have been well established there.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The coastal city also benefited in the past 40 years from major construction programs such as Antigone, Port Marianne and Odysseum districts.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The city is situated on hilly ground 10 km (6 mi) inland from the Mediterranean coast, on the river Lez.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier is located 170 km (106 mi) from Marseille, 242 km (150 mi) from Toulouse, and 748 km (465 mi) from Paris.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The city is relatively close to Nîmes, being just 50 km (31 mi).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier's highest point is the Place du Peyrou, at an altitude of 57 m (187 ft).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The city is built on two hills, Montpellier and Montpelliéret, thus some of its streets have great differences of altitude.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Some of its streets are also very narrow and old, which gives it a more intimate feel.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier has a Mediterranean climate (Köppen *Csa*), with cool, damp winters, and hot, rather dry summers.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The monthly mean ranges from 7.2 °C (45.0 °F) in January to 24.1 °C (75.4 °F) in July.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Precipitation is around 630 millimetres (24.8 in), and is greatest in fall and winter, but not absent in summer, either.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Since 2001, Montpellier has been divided into seven official neighbourhoods, themselves divided into sub-neighbourhoods.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Each of them possesses a neighbourhood council.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The whole metropolitan area had a population of 813,272 at the 2020 census.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In a study made by INSEE from 2017 to 2023 Montpellier saw the strongest population growth of France's cities with more than 100,000 inhabitants (+1.4%).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] For most of its history, and even today, Montpellier has been known for its significant Spanish population, heritage and influence.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier also houses significant Moroccan, Algerian, and Italian communities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The University of Montpellier is one of the oldest in the world, founded in 1160, and having been granted a charter in 1220 by Cardinal Conrad von Urach and confirmed by Pope Nicholas IV in a papal bull of 1289.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] It was suppressed during the French Revolution but was re-established in 1896.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] It is not known exactly at what date the schools of literature were founded which developed into the Montpellier faculty of arts; it may be that they were a direct continuation of the Gallo-Roman schools.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The school of law was founded by Placentinus, a doctor from Bologna University, who came to Montpellier in 1160, taught there during two different periods, and died there in 1192.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] With regard to the school of medicine, there were excellent physicians at Montpellier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The statutes given in 1220 by Cardinal Conrad, legate of Honorius III, which were completed in 1240 by Pierre de Conques, placed this school under the direction of the Bishop of Maguelonne.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Pope Nicholas IV issued a Bull in 1289, combining all the schools into a university, which was placed under the direction of the bishop, but which in fact enjoyed a large measure of autonomy.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Theology was at first taught in the convents, in which St.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Anthony of Padua, Raymond Lullus, and the Dominican Bernard de la Treille lectured.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Two letters of King John prove that a faculty of theology existed at Montpellier independently of the convents, in January 1350.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] By a Bull of 17 December 1421, Martin V granted canonical institution to this faculty and united it closely with the faculty of law.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] In the 16th century the faculty of theology disappeared for a time, when Calvinism, in the reign of Henry II of France, held complete possession of the city.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] It resumed its functions after Louis XIII had reestablished the royal power at Montpellier in 1622; but the rivalries of Dominicans and Jesuits interfered seriously with the prosperity of the faculty, which disappeared at the Revolution.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The faculty numbered among its illustrious pupils of law Petrarch, who spent four years at Montpellier, and among its lecturers Guillaume de Nogaret, chancellor to Philip the Fair, Guillaume de Grimoard, afterwards pope under the name of Urban V, and Pedro de Luna, antipope as Benedict XIII.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] But after the 15th century this faculty fell into decay, as did also the faculty of arts, although for a time, under Henry IV of France, the latter faculty had among its lecturers Isaac Casaubon.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The Montpellier school of medicine owed its success to the ruling of the Guilhems, lords of the town, by which any licensed physician might lecture there; there was no fixed limit to the number of teachers, lectures were multiplied, and there was a great wealth of teaching.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Rabelais took his medical degrees at Montpellier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] It was in this school that the biological theory of vitalism, elaborated by Barthez (1734–1806), had its origin.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The French Revolution did not interrupt the existence of the faculty of medicine.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The faculties of science and of letters were re-established in 1810; that of law in 1880.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] It was on the occasion of the sixth centenary of the university, celebrated in 1889, that the Government of France announced its intention—which has since been realized—of reorganizing the provincial universities in France.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] With 70,000 students and good universities whose influence radiates worldwide, as well as very prestigious schools, the capital of Hérault is a fantastic setting for a post-baccalaureate course.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] University of Montpellier 1 and University of Montpellier 2 reunified in January 2015 to form the University of Montpellier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Paul Valéry University Montpellier, remains a separate entity.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Moreover, Montpellier was ranked 137th best student city in the world for 2026, according to QS Best Student Cities 2025 ranking.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier is served by railway, including TGV highspeed trains.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier's main railway station is Saint-Roch.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Since 2018, there is also a station on the high-speed railway linking Nîmes and Montpellier with the LGV Méditerranée, called Montpellier-Sud de France.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The Montpellier – Méditerranée Airport is located in the area of Fréjorgues, in the town of Mauguio, southeast of Montpellier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The *Transports de l'agglomération de Montpellier* (TaM) manages the city's public transportation, including its 56-kilometre (35 mi) tramway network consisting of five lines and several parking facilities.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Line 1 runs from Mosson in the west to Odysseum in the east.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Line 2 runs from Jacou in the northeast to St.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Line 3, which is 22.4-kilometre (13.9 mi) long, links Juvignac and Pérols with a branch to Lattes and serves 32 stations.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Line 4 circles the centre and serves as a connector line between the various arms of tram system.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Since 2019, €440 million were invested into the construction of a 5th tramway line, linking the south from Lavérune to Clapiers, up north.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] It has been inaugurated on December 20, 2025.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Since 21 December 2023, the public transport is free for all residents.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Previously, all residents under 18 and over 65 years of age have been transported free of charge since 1 September 2021.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The TaM also manages the large bike sharing scheme Vélomagg', started in June 2007, comprising 1200 bicycles and 50 stations.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier was the finish of Stage 11 and the departure of Stage 12 in the 2007 Tour de France.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] It was also the finish of Stage 11 and the departure of Stage 12 in the 2016 edition.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier was one of the hosts of the FIBA EuroBasket 2015.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The city is home to the Open Sud de France tennis tournament since 2010, and will host the XXXI World Rhythmic Gymnastics Championship.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The main athletics stadium is the Philippidès Stadium, which is owned by the University of Montpellier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The city is a centre for cultural events as there are many students.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Montpellier has two large concert venues: Le Zénith Sud (7.000 seats) and L'Arena (14.000 seats).
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Le Corum cultural and conference centre contains three auditoriums.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The name Montpellier is used for towns and streets in as many as four continents.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Many places in the United Kingdom and Ireland carry the name Montpellier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Often they are in resort locations claiming some of the healthy attributes for which the French city was renowned in earlier centuries.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The variant spelling "Montpelier" is common, and is of quite early provenance.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The first example was the early 19th-century suburb of Montpelier in Brighton.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] The capital of the American state of Vermont was named Montpelier because of the high regard in which the Americans held the French who had aided their Revolutionary War against the British.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Several other American cities are also named Montpelier.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] Places named Montpellier/Montpelier are also found in Australia, Canada, South Africa, and the Caribbean.
[src:angelica-schwall-düren/montpellier] James Madison, the United States fourth president, named his plantation Montpelier (Orange, Virginia), after the resort-like properties associated with the city at the time.
